<HEADLINE> N.Y teacher's starting, average salaries third-best in U.S.  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - New York's average teachers' salary is
third-best in the nation and more than 22 percent over the national
average, according to figures compiled by the American Federation
of Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   New York's average teacher salary of $49,686 a year trailed only
New Jersey ($51,692) and Connecticut ($50,277) during the 1998-99
school year, according to American Federation of Teachers
statistics.
</P>
<P>
   The national teacher salary average for that school year was
$40,574, the AFT said.
</P>
<P>
   New York was also third in terms of average starting teacher
salary in 1998-99 at $30,808, trailing Alaska ($32,884) and
Connecticut ($31,391). The national average there was $26,639.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics were released Wednesday as part of the AFT's
annual convention in Philadelphia. New York's largest teachers'
union, New York State United Teachers, is affiliated with the AFT.
</P>
<P>
   New York State United Teachers has warned about an impending
shortage of teachers in New York, blaming teacher salaries in the
state in part, and detailed the dissatisfaction of many educators
with their paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   In a March survey, 62 percent of New York State United Teachers'
members polled disagreed with the statement, ''I feel that I am
paid fairly for the work I do as a teacher.'' Among New York City
teachers, 86 percent disagreed with the statement.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the AFT, New Yorker Sandra Feldman, said the
national figures in her union's survey indicate that what she
called low teacher salaries nationwide are threatening to thwart
the attainment of higher academic standards.
</P>
<P>
   The AFT said the average annual starting salary for teachers in
1999 badly trailed those for other new college graduates such as in
engineering ($44,362), computer sciences ($42,500) and
economics-finance ($38,234).
</P>
<P>
   ''New college graduates as well as seasoned teachers are being
lured to other professions with handsome salary offers while the
teaching profession often isn't even in the horse race,'' Feldman
said.
</P>
<P>
   That was one way of looking at the numbers. But a group
representing the teachers' employers in New York, the state School
Boards Association, interpreted the state's No. 3 finishes in both
average salary and starting salary as a sign ''New York is paying
competitive salaries in comparison with other states,'' school
boards spokesman David Ernst said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think teachers are rewarded amply in New York and we're
getting a good supply of teachers,'' Ernst said. ''We are getting a
lot of good people coming into the teaching ranks.''
</P>
<P>
   While there are ''spot'' shortages of teachers in some areas and
in some subjects like mathematics and science, Ernst said ''there
is no general shortage of teachers'' in New York.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the state Legislature has channeled unprecedented
sums of education aid to schools in recent years - a record $1.2
billion increase in the current fiscal year alone - helping to
account for New York's higher-than-average pay for teachers.
</P>
<P>
   For a generation, he said, school districts have tended to
increase the pay scales for middle- and high-salaried teachers
higher than for beginning teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Both unions and school boards have to pay attention to that,''
Ernst said. ''There is a finite amount of money. You've got to
decide, where does the new money absolutely need to go? I think
there is a valid argument that can be made that starting salaries
need to be higher in certain areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the 100 largest cities nationally, Yonkers ($37,045) had
the highest starting teachers' salary in the United States for
school year 1998-99, according to the American Federation of
Teachers' data. Rochester ($31,500) was 15th, New York City
($30,265) was 23rd and Buffalo ($28,563) was 36th.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
