<HEADLINE> City seeking to maximize tourism clings to gangster's tale  </HEADLINE>
AP Photo
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Trying to snatch a tourism opportunity
before it's stolen by time, one community hopes to make a hit with
its once-famous gangster.
</P>
<P>
   Seven decades ago in the days of Prohibition and speakeasies,
Jack ''Legs'' Diamond was a ruthless and colorful gangster with a
national reputation. The flashy gangster enjoyed a notoriety
similar to that of organized crime boss John Gotti - New York
City's ''Dapper Don'' - today. But Diamond was Albany's own, said
Herb Holland, who will lead the offbeat tour July 19.
</P>
<P>
   And Albany wants to make sure he stays that way.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most of the adults, particularly if they're middle-aged and
older, will know Legs Diamond,'' said Holland, a retired educator.
But, he adds, ''As time goes on, the number of people who know of
him will become fewer and fewer.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He did things that fascinated people,'' Holland told The Daily
Gazette of Schenectady. Diamond was ''a very cruel guy ... He
thought nothing of killing people who got in his way.'' His way was
to run alcohol illegally through the Catskills and much of New York
state.
</P>
<P>
   The tour comes at a time when tourism is hot for criminals.
</P>
<P>
   The just-released book ''Crime Scene USA'' is a guide to murder
and mayhem in every state. More than 150 crime scenes are listed
including the scenes of assassinations of President Kennedy, John
Lennon and Martin Luther King Jr., the homes of JonBenet Ramsey and
Nicole Brown Simpson, and the sites of Wild West hangouts and
holdups of outlaw Jesse James.
</P>
<P>
   Now Albany, the one-time home to historical figures including
presidents Martin Van Buren, Grover Cleveland, Theodore Roosevelt
and Franklin D. Roosevelt, is hoping Diamond is yet another draw
for history-minded tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ''Here we had a nationally known crime figure who actually
operated in and around Albany to say nothing of being killed
here,'' Holland said.
</P>
<P>
   That death is a big part of the story - and the tour.
</P>
<P>
   Among the attractions is the site of the speakeasy where Diamond
celebrated his acquittal on kidnapping charges on the night of his
death by a gunman. Now it's a state office building. The hotel
ballroom where Diamond hung out is no longer around, either. The
once glamorous Kenmore Hotel is now used for office space. And the
two-story brick row building where Diamond spent his final hours is
still there, although it is now a private home, not a rooming
house.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 19, 1931, hundreds of people gathered outside the
rooming house after news spread that Diamond had been shot dead
there.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was a national celebrity that got killed, that got
murdered,'' Holland said.
</P>
<P>
   Diamond's killer was never captured.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
