<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The great anagram searchers: Scrabble addicts test skills in Albany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   COLONIE, N.Y. (AP) - Jan Dixon can't drive without forming words
from the license plate letters on cars ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Introductions to new people are excuses to turn names into
anagrams, rearranging letters to form words and sentences.
</P>
<P>
   So when Dixon discovered Scrabble tournaments in 1977, the
Wilmington, Del., resident had found her niche. ''This is what I've
been waiting for all my life,'' she said. ''These people are nuts,
just like me. You have to realize this game is a sickness.''
</P>
<P>
   Dixon, and 70-some other people with a fondness for shuffling
wooden tiles on game boards spent their Fourth of July competing in
the Fifth Annual Nor'Easter Scrabble Tournament held at a Marriott
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that could be heard over the low clink of the
plastic-coated pieces on Monday as the game began was a constant
stream of ''Shhhhsh.''
</P>
<P>
   Sets of two hovered over game boards, exchanging words only to
take turns, calculate scores, and sometimes bluff the opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Stefan Fatsis became so enthralled by the game two years ago
that he began studying word lists in every and any spare moment -
on the subway, in the bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   He even took a year's leave from his job as a sports business
reporter to write a book about the vocabulary game invented in
1948.
</P>
<P>
   With the prize purses that most Scrabble tournaments offer, it
would be hard to play the game to the exclusion of all else,
however.
</P>
<P>
   The national tournament in Providence has a purse of $25,000 for
the winner of the expert category. In the contest staged just
outside Albany, the top prize was just $400.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Pfeiffer, a fire safety consultant from New York City who
coordinated the tournament, said most do not play for the money.
</P>
<P>
   ''People play because they are addicted,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
