<HEADLINE> Lazio honors vets, marches in three parades to mark July Fourth  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TICONDEROGA, N.Y. (AP) - Republican Senate candidate Rick Lazio
was marching in three Fourth of July parades in northern New York
on Tuesday while trumpeting his accomplishments for veterans in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to pointing at his own record, Lazio's campaign
pressed its criticism of his Democratic opponent, Hillary Rodham
Clinton, who was with President Clinton in New York City observing
OpSail.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's out taking an aircraft carrier for a vanity cruise and
we're out here on Main Street,'' said Lazio political strategist
Mike Murphy. ''I think it really tells the story of the difference
in the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   At a breakfast for Korean War veterans in Saratoga Springs
earlier Tuesday, Lazio himself questioned the first lady's
commitment to veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it goes back to, you know, 'What have you done for New
York?''' Lazio said. ''When New York needed Mrs. Clinton to fight
for veterans health benefits, where was she?''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio also publicized his support for a number of
veterans-related initiatives in Congress and also claimed he has
fought Clinton administration efforts to divert funding for
veterans benefits from New York to ''southern states like Arkansas
and Tennessee.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I went to the floor of the House and succeeded in obtaining a
commitment that New Yorkers would get their fair share, plus a
modest increase in funding,'' Lazio said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rick Lazio's rhetoric doesn't match his record,'' Clinton
campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson said in a statement. ''While
Hillary Clinton worked to make treating Gulf War illness a
government priority, Rick Lazio was voting (in 1995) to cut $1
billion from the Administration's veterans budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the Saratoga Springs Italian American War Veteran's
Post, Lazio also said he is sponsoring legislation that would have
the U.S. government acknowledge that Italian-Americans were victims
of discrimination and were even interned at times during World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio called it ''a black mark on American history, and on our
freedom, our rights. There was no due process, there was no trial.
People were detained for long periods of time, many times it was
months on end.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his legislation does not call for a government apology.
''It would simply call for a recognition that this act happened,
and an educational process using our agencies to make sure our
Americans understand what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The Long Island congressman, who is on the second leg of a
five-day bus tour across the state, was warmly received in Fourth
of July parades in the Adirondack towns of Argyle and Ticonderoga.
</P>
<P>
   Les Bristol, an 88-year-old veteran of the World War II Battle
of the Bulge, stood on the curb outside his house and Lazio - as he
did many times at the marches - went over and shook his hand.
</P>
<P>
   When asked later if he planned to vote for the congressman,
Bristol, who was a little hard of hearing, said ''Of course I am.
He's a good man.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Ticonderoga parade, people stood three and four deep
along the sidewalks and cheered heartily as Lazio and his wife,
Pat, marched past, accompanied by Rep. John Sweeney, R-Saratoga
County.
</P>
<P>
   At least one supporter from the opposition managed to enter the
line of march briefly carrying a sign for Clinton. Louis Morett
said he's a lifelong Democrat who ''believes in competition.''
Lazio, he said, is ''a good man. There's a lot of things about
Hillary Clinton I don't like - like late-term abortion - but you
have to have competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Tuesday, Lazio ended his day with a parade in Lake Placid.
His ''Mainstream Express'' tour moves on to Plattsburgh, Burke,
Malone, Massena, Watertown and Syracuse on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
