<HEADLINE> Flights To Solomon Islands Canceled  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONIARA, Solomon Islands (AP) -- The last international airline
still flying into the embattled Solomon Islands canceled its only
flight into the capital Wednesday as ethnic fighting again
escalated.
</P>
<P>
   Papua New Guinea carrier Air Nuigini said insurance companies
refused to provide cover for the flights into Honiara after rebels
from the island of Malaita fought running battles with rival
Isatabus from the main island of Guadalcanal.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have been engaged in a fierce battle in an area
around Alligator Creek, east of Honiara and close to the city's
international airport.
</P>
<P>
   At least two Isatabu fighters were killed on Monday when
Malaitans drove a bulldozer reinforced with armor plating and
mounted machine guns across a bridge that previously had separated
the two sides and began attacking.
</P>
<P>
   There were also reports of Malaitan fighters attacking civilians
and forcing them from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The renewed fighting -- which shattered a two-week truce -- stems
from a dispute between the Malaitans and the Isatabus, who have
expelled 20,000 migrants from Malaita who sought jobs and land on
Guadalcanal. Up to 60 people have been killed in 19 months of
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes for peace were raised last Friday when a new prime
minister, Manasseh Sogavare, was elected who pledged to convene
fresh peace talks. But since then, the Isatabu rebels have said
they do not recognize Sogavare's government, calling the election
rigged by Malaitans.
</P>
<P>
   In another blow to the peace process, the new opposition, led by
former Prime Minister Bartholomew Ulufa'alu, said it may launch a
legal challenge to the new government's legitimacy. Six of his
members in parliament claim they did not attend the vote at which
Sogavare was elected by a narrow majority because they were
threatened by Malaitan rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Ulufa'alu resigned after being seized at gunpoint by Malaitan
rebels.
</P>
</TEXT>
