<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nevada Road Reopened in Protest  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA CHEREB
<TEXT>
<P>
   JARBIDGE, Nev. (AP) -- Protesters from around the West and as far
away as the East Coast spent Independence Day reopening a dirt road
in a national forest in defiance of the U.S. Forest Service.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds joined a ''tug-of-war'' line tied to a boulder the
protesters dubbed the ''Liberty Rock.'' The boulder blocked access
to a stretch of road leading to campgrounds and a wilderness area
in a remote corner of northeastern Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Chanting ''Freedom, Freedom,'' the Shovel Brigade moved the
boulder inch-by-inch Tuesday. The crowd cheered as the rock was
removed and a pickup truck carrying 90-year-old Helen Wilson, the
oldest resident in Jarbidge, drove over the 900-foot section of
reopened road.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can see what people power does,'' said John Carpenter, a
state legislator from Elko. ''People power can move these rocks and
it can move the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The demonstration was the latest chapter in a dispute between
Washington officials and locals upset with federal land policy. The
brigade claims the county owns the narrow dirt road and the Forest
Service is the intruder.
</P>
<P>
   South Canyon Road was washed out in a flood in 1995. Federal
authorities have blocked efforts to reopen it, fearing road repairs
would jeopardize habitat of the threatened bull trout, which is
protected under the Endangered Species Act.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a federal judge denied an injunction sought by the
Justice Department to halt the rally, but warned members of the
brigade they could be prosecuted for any environmental damage.
</P>
<P>
   Though the road was not completely rebuilt and the turnout was
far less than the 5,000 some had predicted, organizers claimed
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ''Their fight is my fight back there,'' said Scott Traudt, 34, a
commercial fisherman from Warwick, R.I. who said loggers, ranchers
and others like himself who make their living from the land are
frustrated by increased government regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've had enough. We're all getting unified.''
</P>
<P>
   The only environmentalists at the gathering was a group called
''The Old Broads for Wilderness.''
</P>
<P>
   ''They're making a mess to make a point about the federal
government,'' said the group's executive director, Susan Tixier.
''I don't think the Forest Service is always right, but here they
did the right thing closing the road.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Jarbidge Shovel Brigade: http://www.jarbidgeshovelbrigade.com
</P>
<P>
   Forest Service: http://www.fs.fed.us
</P>
</TEXT>
