<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, July 5, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Western Slope Fires Surge
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CRAIG, Colo. (AP) -- Two wildfires on Colorado's Western Slope surged forward
Tuesday in conditions so dry that brush burning at one location was likened to
kindling. A blaze in the Dinosaur National Monument in remote northwestern
Colorado was burning an estimated 9,000 acres, while a smaller fire about 35
miles southwest of Grand Junction had consumed about 2,500 acres. Winds were
reported at 20 mph at several points and temperatures ranged into the 90s. The
Dinosaur blaze, which began Monday, was burning mostly on federal land, said
Lynn Barclay, spokeswoman with the Craig Interagency Dispatch center. No
structures were immediately threatened.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Prosecutor Opens Echelon Probe
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- A French prosecutor has opened a preliminary investigation into
a U.S.-led spy network that has left many Europeans suspicious that their
businesses are being monitored, judicial sources said Tuesday. Paris prosecutor
Jean-Pierre Dintilhac in May asked the DST, France's internal security service,
to carry out the preliminary inquiry, according to a report in Tuesday's Le
Figaro newspaper. The report was confirmed by judicial sources who spoke on
condition they not be named. The Echelon issue surfaced in February when a
European Parliament report discussed the existence and activities of the
network, whose members also include Britain, Canada, Australia and New Zealand.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rogue Rio Police Suspended
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- In a campaign to clean up its police force, a
state government in Brazil fired or suspended 353 police officers linked to such
crimes as car theft, torture and murder. Many of the officers had been convicted
but were allowed to keep working as they appealed their convictions. Garotinho
said he had prepared a second list of 70 prison guards and 38 firefighters who
would be suspended Wednesday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Peru President To Keep Chief Near
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- President Alberto Fujimori pledged Tuesday to keep his
shadowy security chief by his side, denying reports that the Organization of
American States urged him to fire Vladimiro Montesinos. ''Montesinos will
continue his functions as adviser at the top level of the intelligence
service,'' Fujimori said of the man widely feared for a spy network and seen by
many as the power behind the president. The statement broadcast late Tuesday
came five days after a top-level OAS delegation urged Fujimori to reform Peru's
damaged democracy following his tainted re-election.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fiji Military Defuses Troop Protest
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- The military quelled a protest by troops at a Fiji army
base Wednesday, but said local chiefs threatened disturbances in support of
rebels who have been holding 27 people hostage for seven weeks. Two or three
soldiers who were sympathetic to rebel leader George Speight had confiscated
arms and ammunition Tuesday inside the base at Labasa, on the northern island of
Vanua Levu. ''All of the arms are back in the armory and the soldiers have
resumed normal duty,'' Lt. Col. Filipo Tarakinikini told The Associated Press.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian Pays Visit to Hometown
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- Without the hordes of journalists who chronicled his movements
in the United States, Elian Gonzalez Tuesday made a quiet visit to his hometown
for the first time since returning to Cuba last week, the government said
afterward. Accompanied by his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, Elian visited the
homes of his paternal and maternal grandparents in Cardenas, about 90 miles east
of Havana, state television reported. Elian also stopped by his school, where he
will resume his studies in the fall, and played with several of his schoolmates
before he and his family returned to Havana later in the day.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mexico's President-Elect Lays Out Plans
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexico's president-elect Tuesday laid out sweeping plans
for a new justice system, a more human rights-oriented foreign policy and a
multiparty Cabinet. Opposition leader Vicente Fox, who won Sunday's presidential
elections, also pledged to eliminate the posturing and tension in U.S.-Mexico
relations over the two countries' border, where immigration-related incidents
have sometimes broken into violence in recent months.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Royals Beat White Sox 10-7
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Jermaine Dye marked his All-Star selection with a
home run and the Kansas City Royals stopped Chicago's team-record road winning
streak at 12, defeating the White Sox 10-7 Tuesday night. Ray Durham and Jose
Valentin began the game with home runs for the White Sox. Mark Quinn and Dave
McCarty also homered for the Royals and Johnny Damon drove in three runs. Kansas
City has won only six times in its last 21 games, but is 4-1 against Chicago --
the team with the best record in the majors.
AP NewsBrief by PAULINE M. MILLARD 
</P>
