<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, July 5, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fires Roar in Colorado
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CRAIG, Colo. (AP) -- Two wildfires on Colorado's Western Slope surged forward
Tuesday in conditions so dry that brush burning at one location was likened to
kindling. A blaze in the Dinosaur National Monument in remote northwestern
Colorado was burning an estimated 9,000 acres, while a smaller fire about 35
miles southwest of Grand Junction had consumed about 2,500 acres. Winds were
reported at 20 mph at several points and temperatures ranged into the 90s. The
Dinosaur blaze, which began Monday, was burning mostly on federal land. No
structures were immediately threatened.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Protestants Menace North Ireland
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Masked youths set vehicles ablaze and
police traded gunshots with protesters in a Protestant area of Belfast Tuesday,
as anti-Catholic extremists menaced the streets of Northern Ireland for a second
straight night. Rage flared as the British territory braced for more violent
Protestant protest over British authorities' determination to restrict
traditional parades in Catholic areas. The paramilitary outlaws coordinating the
mayhem from behind the scenes have warned that rioting will intensify if the
Orange Order, a legal Protestant fraternal group, isn't allowed to conduct a
banned march through the main Catholic district of Portadown on Sunday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Prosecutor Opens Echelon Probe
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- A French prosecutor has opened a preliminary investigation into
a U.S.-led spy network that has left many Europeans suspicious that their
businesses are being monitored, judicial sources said Tuesday. Paris prosecutor
Jean-Pierre Dintilhac in May asked the DST, France's internal security service,
to carry out the preliminary inquiry, according to a report in Tuesday's Le
Figaro newspaper. The Echelon issue surfaced in February when a European
Parliament report discussed the existence and activities of the network, whose
members also include Britain, Canada, Australia and New Zealand.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fiji Military Defuses Troop Protest
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- The military quelled a protest by troops at a Fiji army
base Wednesday, but said local chiefs threatened disturbances in support of
rebels who have been holding 27 people hostage for seven weeks. Two or three
soldiers who were sympathetic to rebel leader George Speight had confiscated
arms and ammunition Tuesday inside the base at Labasa, on the northern island of
Vanua Levu. ''All of the arms are back in the armory and the soldiers have
resumed normal duty,'' Lt. Col. Filipo Tarakinikini told The Associated Press.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian Pays Visit to Hometown
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- Without the hordes of journalists who chronicled his movements
in the United States, Elian Gonzalez Tuesday made a quiet visit to his hometown
for the first time since returning to Cuba last week, the government said
afterward. Accompanied by his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, Elian visited the
homes of his paternal and maternal grandparents in Cardenas, about 90 miles east
of Havana, state television reported. Elian also stopped by his school, where he
will resume his studies in the fall, and played with several of his schoolmates
before he and his family returned to Havana later in the day.
</P>
