<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taos Artist Show Tells Tale of Art  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD BENKE
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAOS, N.M. (AP) -- Indians settled in the lap of their
13,000-foot mountain 1,000 years ago. Spaniards brought trade and
religion 600 years later. Mountain men sought bear, beaver,
buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Then came a century of artists, hunting images and leaving a
historical record of once-wild Taos as a cultural phenomenon. The
documentary evidence is all wrapped up in a neat package at the
Albuquerque Museum, where an exhibition, ''Taos Artists and Their
Patrons,'' runs through Aug. 6, then opens in San Antonio, Texas,
Sept. 12.
</P>
<P>
   The real thing is still here, too, along these old, narrow,
adobe-lined streets 150 miles north of the museum. The plaza
emporium depicted by J. Ward Lockwood's 1931 painting is still open
for business, selling T-shirts, Indian-type drums and other
souvenirs. The old cemetery painted by Barbara Latham in 1944 is
still adorned with flowers and mementoes. And the elegant adobe
structures of Taos Pueblo painted by Walter Ufer in 1917 still draw
thousands of tourists annually.
</P>
<P>
   The first of the Taos Artists, Ernest Blumenschein and Bert G.
Phillips, arrived in 1898. One of their wagon wheels broke 20 miles
from town. Blumenschein carried the wheel, on horseback, into Taos
for repairs.
</P>
<P>
   The two Eastern artists, enthralled, painted many canvases here
in the ensuing 30 years. Blumenschein came and went. Phillips never
left.
</P>
<P>
   ''That started off the whole art colony,'' Taos Mayor Fred
Peralta says. ''It's a time that kind of put Taos on the map, in
the sense of the outside world learning about this community.''
</P>
<P>
   The artists brought their friends and their friends' friends to
Taos.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think they were kind of captivated by the landscapes that
were painted by the artists here,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But art was already here when Bert and Blumy arrived -- the
valley has been continuously inhabited for about 1,000 years. It
flourished long before the Spaniards came in 1600, before the
trappers arrived in the 1830s, before New Mexico was purchased by
the United States in 1848.
</P>
<P>
   Today, art to Taos is more than just a pretty picture -- it's
bread and butter.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would have to say it is a really major influence. It could
be as much as 25 percent of our economy,'' Peralta says.
</P>
<P>
   The Taos phenomenon didn't just happen by itself. There was no
art market here in 1898. The Taos Society of Artists had to create
a market, and did. The group had patrons like John D. Rockefeller
Jr., Phoebe Apperson Hearst, Mabel Dodge Luhan and the Santa Fe
Railway, among many.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Fe Railway marketing agent William Haskell Simpson used
the paintings in a promotional campaign that glamorized the
Southwest as a desirable destination. So the railroad subsidized
the art colony and created a tourist influx that helped grow the
town.
</P>
<P>
   From 1916 to 1926, too, the artists organized traveling
exhibitions that usually opened in New York City and worked their
way West, closing at the Fine Arts Museum in Santa Fe.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the museum show's featured artists who followed Phillips
and Blumenschein include Oscar Berninghaus, John Marin, Victor
Higgins, Robert Henri, Howard Cook and Eanger Irving Couse. Their
paintings, on loan for the show from museums around the country,
captured Indian and Hispanic traditions in detail.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips' ''Penitente Burial Procession'' shows the sweep of
Taos Valley as a line of mourners stretches for a mile along a
curving path, on foot, led by three crosses and the casket borne on
four men's shoulders. Couse's ''Wal-si-el'' depicts an Indian
kneeling before a hot ''kiva'' hearth beside a classically painted
pueblo pot. Berninghaus' ''Peace and Plenty'' shows two Indians and
their harvest bounty.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 paintings are in the show, spanning 1898 to 1950,
said Ellen Landis, curator of art at the Albuquerque Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The artists, she said, were in a unique position to see the real
Taos.
</P>
<P>
   ''Because they lived there, because they were friends of so many
people, they were offered the opportunity to see things --
traditions, cultural and ethnic, that a stranger wouldn't have the
opportunity to see,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many other artists who worked here after the Taos Society
disbanded in 1927, such as Georgia O'Keeffe, contributed to the
record of Taos, even if not to the show. O'Keeffe, who stayed with
Mabel Dodge Luhan, painted the back of the San Francisco de Asis
Church near Taos, and it remains an art and tourism icon. She
painted the Lawrence Tree, a large ponderosa pine outside D.H.
Lawrence's cabin north of town, and it became a familiar image and
tourist draw, as well.
</P>
<P>
   There are nearly 100 art galleries and 1,000 artists in this
small northern New Mexico town of 6,000 people, which is a ski
resort in the winter and a hiking-fishing-sightseeing resort in
summers.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's interesting about Taos, too, is that it's often seen as
a center of revolt against intruders, a bit more radical than the
other pueblos,'' says Paul Andrew Hutton, a historian at the
University of New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   There had been pueblo uprisings in 1680 and again in 1847.
</P>
<P>
   These new artistic intruders, though, got along fine with the
Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ''Maybe that's because they weren't always trying to impose
their will,'' Hutton says, adding the edginess of the pueblo seemed
to appeal to the freethinking artists.
</P>
<P>
   Territorial Gov. Charles Bent and 20 others were killed in the
pueblo revolt of 1847. Bent died in his house, which is now an art
gallery.
</P>
<P>
   If there was any single thing that transformed Taos from
isolated aerie to tourist Mecca, Hutton says, ''it's art.''
</P>
<P>
   That and the automobile, adds Mayor Peralta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
