<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Century of Jorge Luis Borges  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL MELIA
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- Barely into his afterlife,
Argentina's foremost writer is striding toward immortality.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 50 years until his death in 1986, Jorge Luis
Borges produced short stories, poems and essays in a precise,
almost mathematical style that set the standard for a generation of
Spanish-language writers.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is the subject of a new documentary, his writings are
praised as far away as New York, Tokyo and London and, last year, a
posthumous collection of his essays won a National Book Critics
Circle Award.
</P>
<P>
   A century after his birth, Borges is back -- his works now
ushering in generations of new readers to the surreal labyrinths of
his mind.
</P>
<P>
   His writings still beckon with the allure of magical worlds, of
intertwining realities as much the enigmatic creations of his
imagination as his own interpretation of a Buenos Aires of long
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''Borges is great. ... He's one of the greatest of the 20th
century,'' says Roberto Gonzalez Echevarria, a literature professor
at Yale University who ranks the writer among T.S. Eliot and Ezra
Pound.
</P>
<P>
   He credits Borges with creating his own genre through meticulous
attention to language, and with uniquely enveloping his musings
inside detective stories, essays and adventure tales.
</P>
<P>
   ''The short story that is an essay and the essay that is a short
story, and also a brain teaser -- that brought to light one of the
dilemmas of the 20th century: The more we understand about
language, the less we know about language itself,'' Echevarria
says.
</P>
<P>
   Works such as ''El Aleph'' and ''Fictions'' blended fact and
fiction in masterful, dreamlike atmospheres. Several Latin American
''magical realists'' later praised Borges for pioneering that
style. As a contributor to the modernist dialogue, he also made his
presence known in other areas, from translation to political
satire.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Borges produced more than 35 volumes of writings and his
works were translated into dozens of languages, winning him many
major literary awards. Only the Nobel Prize proved elusive.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1999, centennial celebrations of the writer's birth
cast new attention on his works. Fans toasted the 100th anniversary
with art exhibits, poetry readings and essay prizes. Officials
unveiled a coin emblazoned with the portrait of the famously gaunt
writer and officials dedicated a new museum containing his
manuscripts. Trend-conscious readers even snapped up new editions
of his works.
</P>
<P>
   Borgesmania also reached the United States, where ''Selected
Non-Fictions'' won a National Book Critics Circle Award -- honored
for the collection of essays, lectures and film reviews in
recognition of a broad vision so amply praised in his fiction.
</P>
<P>
   While Borges has made high school readings lists here, he is not
an easy read for everyone, his works difficult to many.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he is read.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know if they understand his books, but they read
them,'' says Juan Jose Sulich, a clerk at a Buenos Aires bookstore
where Borges used to give readings in later life, albeit blind and
bent over his trademark engraved cane.
</P>
<P>
   Tristan Bauer, who made the documentary ''The Books and the
Night,'' sought to explain in the film many of the literary
labyrinths. Bauer is concerned about those who would give up too
easily on Borges.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that's a very grave problem in our society,'' Bauer
says. ''If Argentina produced a writer, a thinker of this
magnitude, I think the people in charge of the culture politically
need to make an effort to promote these figures.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, Borges' reality-transforming works have challenged
readers for generations. His works became popular internationally
after he was ''discovered'' by French intellectuals in the 1950s,
only to be criticized for a time afterward as ''incomprehensible.''
</P>
<P>
   He wrote with scrupulous economy, producing famously concise
stories. His most well-known short story, ''The Aleph,'' brimmed
with insights of his own particular view of the universe in just a
few dozen pages.
</P>
<P>
   Borges carved an erudite path from the age of 6, when he began
devouring the works of Mark Twain, H. G. Wells and Edgar Allan Poe.
From those years in his father's library until his final decades,
when cataracts forced him to rely upon others to read to him, his
world was one of books.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even the most essential experiences of his life -- love,
friendship -- everything was tinged by literature,'' recalls Roberto
Alifano, Borges' former secretary and current editor of the
literary magazine ''Prow,'' which Borges founded in 1922.
</P>
<P>
   After spending his teen-age years in Europe, Borges returned to
Buenos Aires between the two world wars and helped establish a
cultural scene that won favorable comparisons to Paris. His own
literary approach swung from a nationalistic style to a universal
style of his own invention.
</P>
<P>
   Because he chose not to extol the rolling pampas or the gaucho,
or the lifestyle of those Argentine cowboys, many Argentines long
dismissed Borges for the same reason that he shunned tango dancing
and other Argentine cliches: They considered his works a tourist
export.
</P>
<P>
   Borges did look to Europe for his greatest inspiration, but so
did Buenos Aires. While Borges filled his head with the ideas of
Arthur Schopenhauer and Lord Byron, his city looked to Madrid's
Gran Via and Paris' Right Bank. Like his home city, he wasn't
wholly Latin American or European, but uniquely Argentine.
</P>
<P>
   ''One fraction of the population loves him, one fraction hates
him, and the majority in the middle have their doubts,'' says
Flavio Sorbellini, 31, manager of another bookshop.
</P>
<P>
   The political and personal controversies surrounding Borges'
public profile, however, have overshadowed his literary legacy for
many in this capital.
</P>
<P>
   ''Borges was always a very controversial figure in Argentina,''
says Maria Kodama, the author's former student and secretary, whom
he married three weeks before his death. ''I think people are more
interested abroad.''
</P>
<P>
   Though blind from his mid 50s, he continued to stroll the
sidewalks of Buenos Aires, cane in hand and suit jacket buttoned,
well into his 80s. Dozens of books filled with interviews, memoirs
and testimonials produced by still-living friends and former
students have kept his memory fresh.
</P>
<P>
   The memories include controversy, like the award Borges accepted
from Chile's military regime of the 1970s. Scholars have suggested
his reluctance to condemn authoritarian rule may have kept the
Nobel Prize at arm's length.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a small circle of passionate Borges readers is waging
a campaign to draw more attention to his work. But Argentina has
little money available for cultural projects. And promoting a
writer as enigmatic as Borges is not easy.
</P>
<P>
   Nicolas Helft, a 41-year-old computer scientist and Borges fan,
oversees the largest collection of Borges documents in a spare
bedroom of his home. Besides tending thousands of texts,
manuscripts and newspaper clippings, Helft also is co-writing his
fourth book about Borges.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are trying to uncover the links between biography and the
work to help people understand a few fundamental ideas,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Borges' biographer and former friend Maria Esther Vazquez spent
last year traveling through the Argentine interior lecturing on the
author, convinced that an interest in him can be taught.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you explain Borges to them, people get interested,'' says
Vazquez, whose apartment features rare photos of the author
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Borges' current pop-icon celebrity, Vazquez believes
that people will enjoy his work for ''as long as humanity walks the
Earth.'' How many Argentines will appreciate their advanced but
misunderstood patriarch, though, is a question she doesn't want to
answer.
</P>
<P>
   ''What country truly knows its great writers?'' she asks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
