<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five Questions With Jenna Elfman  </HEADLINE>
By LISI de BOURBON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Like any smart investor, Jenna Elfman is
diversifying her portfolio -- her portfolio of characters, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Since she started playing the flighty but lovable Dharma
Finkelstein on the hit ABC sitcom ''Dharma &AMP; Greg,'' the
28-year-old actress has taken on roles that range from a corporate
conquistadora to a model involved in a stormy romance with a
writer.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now people are a little more aware that 'yes, she's an
actress, she's not just one character and she actually can do other
characters,''' Elfman said during a telephone interview. ''I just
feel like I've been introduced, and now I'm rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   She credits ''Keeping the Faith,'' her most recent film, with
lifting her to the next level. She plays Anna Reilly, a successful
businesswoman whose two best friends, a rabbi (Ben Stiller) and a
priest (Edward Norton), fall in love with her.
</P>
<P>
   To play Anna, Elfman had to lower her voice and tone herself
down, no small task for the naturally effervescent and energetic
actress.
</P>
<P>
   ''We did like 13 or 20 takes on one scene because I could not
slow it down enough,'' she said, ''because I thought I was going to
explode if I slowed down that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Elfman, a native of Los Angeles, says she was a talkative
youngster whose mouth was taped shut by one of her teachers to stop
her from speaking during class.
</P>
<P>
   She began studying ballet when she was 5. An injury prevented
her from accepting a spot at a prestigious ballet school. Being
part of a Debbie Allen dance production for the 1991 Academy Awards
was less rewarding than Elfman anticipated, so she turned her
attention to acting. She landed several small TV roles, working as
a backup dancer on ZZ Top's 1994 tour to help pay the bills. Two
years later, she won a role on the short-lived series ''Townies''
with Molly Ringwald.
</P>
<P>
   Elfman starred with Matthew McConaughey, Woody Harrelson, Ellen
DeGeneres and Elizabeth Hurley in ''EDtv.'' ''Town &AMP; Country,'' her
next movie, is scheduled for release in August. It stars Warren
Beatty, Diane Keaton and Goldie Hawn.
</P>
<P>
   1. What was it like to work on ''Town &AMP; Country'' with such
established Hollywood stars?
</P>
<P>
   Elfman: Well, Goldie Hawn for years has been my hero. ... And so
now I'm acting with her after forever going, 'I wish I could be
her, I wish I could be her.' So it was very exciting.
</P>
<P>
   2. What makes ''Dharma &AMP; Greg'' so popular?
</P>
<P>
   Elfman: I think there hasn't been a free-spirited girl who's
purely joyful, purely cares about others, and who's purely sane and
happy on television in a long time.
</P>
<P>
   2&AMP;frac12;. What was the last show that featured one?
</P>
<P>
   Elfman: Per my reality, I'd say 'The Carol Burnett Show.' But
that was variety and they were doing characters. But she was having
fun. She was a good girl, you know. She wasn't neurotic, she wasn't
psychotic, she wasn't insecure, she was just present, and I think
that's refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   3. Why are viewers so drawn to Dharma?
</P>
<P>
   Elfman: Women relate to her because she's probably in their
soul, their inner voice because I think everybody truly is free,
and men dig her because she's cute and has a good sense of humor
and she's not intimidating to women, and also has a good working
marriage that is sexually active. They solve their problems by way
of communication. They honor each other, they admire each other,
and I think people find the hope that they can find that for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   4. What would you like to do in the future?
</P>
<P>
   Elfman: A good variety of roles is probably the ideal because
that's what I love to do. Of course, when you're doing comedy,
comedy, comedy, you want to do drama. When you're doing drama,
drama, drama, you want to do a comedy. I think I've watched other
actresses do this because you sort of want to be taken seriously
and be a 'dramatic actress,' and then the movies never do well and
whatever. So I had a glimpse of wanting to do more drama, of which
I do want to do, but I'm not in a big rush right now. I want to
just keep doing interesting characters; girls that have something
different about them.
</P>
<P>
   5. Where did you get that terrific tan for ''Keeping the
Faith''?
</P>
<P>
   Elfman: Normally, I'm just pale all the time and I don't care,
but I had to go to a tanning bed in SoHo, and oh, I was just laying
there, hearing my skin sizzle, going, 'Why did I ever do this?' And
if I ever had a couple of days, I'd go down to the beach and fry my
skin some more. Yeah, it was a little fake bake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-05-00 1303 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000705.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nashville Sound: Vince Gill  </HEADLINE>
By JIM PATTERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Vince Gill quotes a review of his latest
album: ''He's in love. We're not.'' He laughs, then quotes another:
''He was a much better artist when he was miserable.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm happy, and I'm going to get crucified for it,'' he said
with a shrug. ''I'm just getting ripped. Because it's sappy and
it's lovey-dovey and all those kinds of things.''
</P>
<P>
   At issue is ''Let's Make Sure We Kiss Goodbye,'' an album of
buoyant love songs Gill released in April (MCA).
</P>
<P>
   ''Sure, it sounds like a Hallmark greeting card sometimes,'' he
said. ''But that's how I feel. Life is really sweet. It's really
gentle. Call it corny, call it schmaltzy, call it sappy, call it
all those words, anything you want. It is that, but it feels great.
I like it.''
</P>
<P>
   The album follows Gill's marriage in March to Christian-pop
singer Amy Grant, which came after months of tabloid speculation
and rumors. Grant divorced former TV host Gary Chapman last June,
two years after Gill divorced singer Janis Gill. The events plunged
a guy generally considered a musician's musician and an uncommonly
unaffected country star into tabloid hell.
</P>
<P>
   He declines to give details of the courtship.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think, all in all, I can be proud of how I've handled it,''
Gill said. ''My personal life, I've tried to keep personal and stay
respectful and kind.
</P>
<P>
   ''You won't find me bad-mouthing anybody throughout any of this.
No, it's not always fun. Sometimes you get your belly full of
everybody trying to tell you what you're thinking, what you mean,
and they really don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   It is tough, though, to resist interpreting some of the songs as
hinting at what's going on in Gill's head.
</P>
<P>
   From ''The Luckiest Guy in the World'': ''We watch old movies
and cry at the endings/And get lost in each other's eyes/We hold
hands when we're walking and/Spend all night talking and make love
as the sun starts to rise.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleven of 12 songs on the CD have similar themes. Grant co-wrote
two of the songs. She sings a duet with Gill and appears on the CD
cover kissing him.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gill said it would be wrong to take the album as
literally about his life.
</P>
<P>
   ''It may look personal because of how you perceive my life to
be,'' he said. ''Was a record I made in 1991 as personal just
because you didn't know the current state of my affairs?''
</P>
<P>
   Music critics have compared the album unfavorably with 1998's
''The Key,'' one of the best albums in country music history. While
the new album doesn't measure up, comparing the two isn't fair.
''The Key'' reflects the old standard of soulful, melancholy
country. ''Let's Make Sure We Kiss Goodbye'' is optimistic and
decidedly pop-leaning, and is Gill's first album without the sounds
of steel guitar. It should also be noted that despite its critical
acclaim, singles from ''The Key'' didn't garner much radio airplay,
and sales suffered.
</P>
<P>
   ''(Radio programmers) told me point-blank they didn't want to
play me singing traditional country music,'' Gill said. ''I have an
allegiance with a record company. I have an allegiance to try to
continue to be current, to have hit records. So we made a
contemporary record, in line with what we thought would be
accessible, and having hit records.''
</P>
<P>
   Gill, who isn't touring this year, mixed with fans at the
International Country Music Fan Fair here last month and was
pleased that they were supportive of his music and his personal
life.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that they're thrilled that I'm happy,'' he said. ''I
think they could sense that there was not a real joy going on in me
before.''
</P>
<P>
   After 25 years of riding buses and putting most of his focus on
his career, Gill, 43, said his new marriage has helped him shift
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ''I coached one of Amy's kid's softball teams this spring,'' he
said. ''I'm doing car pools and school functions, just kind of
staying at home and trying to get a workout schedule going. I'm
seeing what life is like without a shaving kit and a bus waiting.
... It's pretty nice.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Official Vince Gill home page is: http://www.vincegill.com/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-05-00 1303 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000705.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kansas Launches Tour, Releases Album  </HEADLINE>
By TOM GARDNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   RENO, Nev. (AP) -- Kansas violinist Robby Steinhardt juggles a
piece of berry pie and an interview effortlessly. He's had plenty
of experience with both in his 28 years with the band.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas was kicking off its Masterworks Tour 2000 of more than
100 dates, the first 30 with fellow progressive rock pioneers Yes.
The tour coincides with the release of ''Somewhere to Elsewhere''
(Magna Carta), the band's 19th album.
</P>
<P>
   The album is ''supposed to dispel all the rumors,'' Steinhardt
said.
</P>
<P>
   What rumors?
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not dead.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the band members, all hovering on either side of 50,
believe Kansas has been reborn now that Kerry Livgren has returned
after a 17-year absence. He wrote all 10 songs and plays guitar and
keyboard on the new CD. Dave Hope, who also left in 1983, plays
bass on two cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's something we've always wanted to do as far as get the
band back together to record,'' said drummer Phil Ehart. ''But the
material had to be right, so we just waited until the right time
came along. The material was right, and we had the time to do it,
and we did it.
</P>
<P>
   ''People say it sounds like the early days of Kansas, but it
sounds modern, like it had been recorded today, so that's good.
It's kind of what we had hoped to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas arrived in 1972 and produced gold albums with ''Kansas,''
''Song for America'' and ''Masque,'' and the platinum
''Leftoverture.'' Hit singles included ''Dust in the Wind,''
''Carry on My Wayward Son'' and ''Point of Know Return.''
</P>
<P>
   The new CD is the first time in nearly two decades that seven
members have recorded together.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we've all matured enough and had enough sidelines --
things to concentrate on and things to do in our lives -- that we're
now more focused on Kansas than ever,'' Steinhardt said. ''The fact
that Kerry wrote all the music means an awful lot.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's writing like he never even did before in Kansas. He's
writing much more than he used to and things just seem to be
flowing out of him. There's music to be proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   Livgren said he enjoyed both the music and the camaraderie
during recording sessions at his studio in rural Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ''I guess we got together to see if we could still do it, and
not only could we still do it, we found that we could do it better
than we ever did.''
</P>
<P>
   They also found 21st-century technology.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was never in the studio for the Kansas album,'' said lead
singer and keyboardist Steve Walsh, who was busy working on a solo
album, touring and spending time with his wife and infant daughter.
He and Livgren swapped CD-ROMs back and forth until they got a
sound they liked. Other members recorded their tracks together and
separately, and all were mixed together.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh hopes to be in the studio for future albums.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I had my druthers, that's the way every album would be
done, because there's something organic that happens,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Changes in band members and audience's tastes left Kansas with a
loyal following, but only occasional success throughout much of the
1980s and '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ''I got on the down side of the curve, I guess,'' said bassist
Billy Greer, who has been with Kansas for more than 16 years. ''But
I've seen some up side. We're just trying to make a career out of
this. We don't know how to do anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for a two-year break from 1983 to 1985, Kansas has been
on the road constantly, doing 100 to 150 concerts a year. Now they
travel by plane, instead of by bus, flying from one show to the
next.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bus days, that was tough,'' Ehart said. ''We were playing
like four and five days a week in sometimes not very good places.
We can be a lot pickier now. So even though there are some bummer
gigs out there, most of them are ones that we kinda hand pick.''
</P>
<P>
   Guitarist Rich Williams said concerts attract a loyal audience.
''This is your record-buying market. It's the people who listen,
who call radios (stations), make requests.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you play at the state fairs, it's just the people who pay
the price of admission to get in, and they happen to be eating a
corn dog and hear the music start and walk by.''
</P>
<P>
   As the band headed toward the stage, Greer said the best part of
the day ''is that one hour, hour and a half, whatever it is, we're
playing. The rest of it is the work part: the travel and the hotel
and being by yourself and away from your family.
</P>
<P>
   ''We get paid to travel. We play for free.''
</P>
<P>
   ------=.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The Web site for Kansas is: http://www.kansasband.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-05-00 1304 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000705.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ribot Finds Energy in Cuban Music  </HEADLINE>
By JAIME HOLGUIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Guitarist Marc Ribot is a musician's musician,
capable of traveling in many directions and unafraid to explore
extremes.
</P>
<P>
   Elvis Costello, Marianne Faithfull and Tom Waits have used his
passionate guitar playing on their albums and tours. His own
projects range from Haitian classical to punk and avant-jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Though disparate, his music is bound, he said, ''by an energy
that I got addicted to when I was very young and heard rock bands
playing in small rooms where everybody's sweating and pushing each
other.
</P>
<P>
   ''That kind of intensity is what I look for.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, Ribot found it in Cuban music, particularly the
work of blind bandleader and tres player Arsenio Rodriguez, whose
career spanned several decades beginning in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was the Jimi Hendrix of his time and place, really pushing
the envelope on what it was possible to play, and that interested
me right away,'' said Ribot, 46, who decided to reinterpret some of
the music.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's band generally included backup singers, large
percussion section, full horn section, piano and tres (a small
double-stringed variant of the guitar). Ribot had only a handful of
musicians to work with, so first he learned the songs as guitar
solos.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the other musicians screwed them up,'' he explained, ''I'd
still be playing something. I could keep it going all by myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, he found four equally proficient musicians in
keyboardist Anthony Coleman, bassist Brad Jones, percussionist E.J.
Rodriguez and drummer Robert J. Rodriguez. During a recent
performance at the Knitting Factory, Los Cubanos Postizos played
with the energy of a punk rock band and the soul of an original
Cuban son band.
</P>
<P>
   That spirit is captured on the new album ''MUY DIVERTIDO! (Very
Entertaining!)'' (Atlantic), a mixture of original material and
interpretations of old Cuban songs. Like its predecessor, ''MUY
DIVERTIDO!'' successfully fuses the sound of New York City's
avant-garde scene, of which Ribot is a leading light, with the
austerity of Cuban folk music.
</P>
<P>
   The quirky percussion and muted melodies of ''Obsession'' are
reminiscent of Ribot's earlier work with the enigmatic crooner
Waits, while ''Baile Baile Baile'' draws from his more discordant
inclinations. On ''Dame Un Cachito Pa'Huele,'' the band reinvents
Rodriguez's 1940s hit, doing for the original what Carlos Santana
did for the Tito Puente-penned classic ''Oye Como Va.''
</P>
<P>
   With the recent popularity of all things Latin, it's not
surprising that Los Cubanos Postizos is Ribot's most successful
solo project to date. Although he welcomes the attention, ''it
upsets me that we seem to have wound up being trendy more than it
upsets anyone else. Basically, we did the first record because it
was fun, and we did the second record because it was still fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Though not a household name, Ribot does carry clout in the music
business, especially within New York City's downtown music scene.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever he wants to try out a new project, he books a gig
somewhere and uses one of the city's performance venues as his
rehearsal space. The results vary depending on his collaborator.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's making discordant atonal squawks with noise
adventurer Mike Patton, plucking lush nylon-stringed melodies with
Peruvian-singer Susana Baca, or creating hip-shaking Cuban rhythms
with his band, Ribot consistently leaves his unique mark.
</P>
<P>
   His musical training began at an early age with family friend
Frantz Casseus, the Haitian classical composer and guitarist.
Casseus played often at the Ribot family home in suburban New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've heard him playing since I was 6 years old,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Though he formally studied with Casseus for three years, ''It's
not like I was some budding 11-year-old classical guitar
virtuoso,'' Ribot said. ''All I wanted to do was play in a garage
rock band.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
