<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baltimore Asks: Why Do You Live Here?  </HEADLINE>
By SHEILA HOTCHKIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- Above the boarded-up rowhouses and battered
storefronts of west Baltimore, a red billboard praises the city to
anyone who looks up from streets rarely visited by tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ''So why do you live here?'' the billboard inquires of those
driving through an area where once elegant townhomes have given way
to drug dens. Seemingly undaunted by its surroundings, the sign
answers in larger letters: ''Pride.''
</P>
<P>
   The message makes 61-year-old Baltimore native James Henry smile
-- a genuine smile, not a cynical one.
</P>
<P>
   ''It tells people who criticize this city something,'' Henry
said, sitting on the concrete stoop of a typical Baltimore
rowhouse. ''I love this city because I was born here, because it's
my mother's home. I love my mother, and she loved this city.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what the ad campaign's creators hoped for when
they plastered various answers to the same question across 74
billboards and 90 buses -- to uncover the hidden pride Baltimoreans
take in their city.
</P>
<P>
   The city figures that if it can get its residents to think more
positively about Baltimore, others will, too.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30,000 responses to the billboards and accompanying
newspaper ads came in during the first four months of the campaign.
The responses praised, among other things, the city's low cost of
living, Orioles baseball and good seafood joints.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we're trying to get people to do is look beyond the
obvious,'' said John Phelan, the Cornerstone Advertising vice
president who created the campaign for the Greater Baltimore
Alliance. ''The disarming thing is if you ask someone the question,
almost no one is going to say something negative.''
</P>
<P>
   Focusing on the positive is a novel concept for Baltimore. The
city has gained national attention for a murder rate that eclipses
that of many larger cities and a syphilis rate that once made
Baltimore the target of Jay Leno's wisecracks for a week.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the derogatory remarks about the city come from an
unlikely source -- Baltimoreans themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ''We tend to overstate the negative and understate the
positive,'' said GBA President Ioanna Morfessis. ''I'm told this is
how Baltimore has always been. But it doesn't mean it always has to
be that way.''
</P>
<P>
   And if Baltimore residents need a reason to change, the GBA has
one for them: The city's self-critical ways reduce its ability to
attract new businesses.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, 50 urban-renewal experts in town for a Johns Hopkins
University-sponsored conference concluded that, despite the success
of the Inner Harbor tourist area, Baltimore lacks the urban
self-esteem it needs to sell itself to the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ''For years, people have let themselves become a part of the
problem. I think now we're letting them be part of the solution,''
Phelan said. ''We wanted to issue people a sort of challenge
because they were creating the negative impression. And if you
create that, and you're so busy believing that, then why do you
live here?''
</P>
<P>
   Cornerstone Advertising posed that question throughout the city
and had people send in their responses, some of which were then
posted on billboards and advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Some were happy with Baltimore for what it is not: ''Because
it's not N.Y., D.C., Philly.'' But Baltimoreans found plenty to be
proud about: ''The infield at Preakness,'' ''Bertha's Mussels,''
''Cal Ripken,'' ''Big city, small town.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the answers strayed well outside the city limits:
''Weekends in O.C.'' (Ocean City), ''Sailing in Annapolis,'' and
''The Terps in March, baby'' (the University of Maryland's
basketball team, the Terrapins).
</P>
<P>
   One of the most frequent responses was recently elected Mayor
Martin O'Malley.
</P>
<P>
   Denise Whiting -- whose restaurant Cafe Hon is a shrine to
everything uniquely Baltimore, from marble steps to painted door
and window screens -- said she has loved the city since she was a
girl.
</P>
<P>
   ''I love the skyline when you're coming from the south,''
Whiting said. ''I love it in the spring, when the trees are all in
bloom.''
</P>
<P>
   Whiting hopes the O'Malley's administration signals a new era
for the city.
</P>
<P>
   ''Any kind of campaign that would promote the city and its
surrounding areas will keep the city moving forward,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.yesbaltimore.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
