<HEADLINE> Israeli-Palestinian Patrols Fight  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA KING
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUSH KATIF JUNCTION, Gaza Strip (AP) -- Some days they mutter
curses in one another's direction. Occasionally they punch each
other out. And now and then, they face off with automatic weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was that Israeli and Palestinian troops would build
trust and keep the peace by patrolling together in the West Bank
and Gaza Strip. It hasn't quite worked out that way.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being a showcase for cooperation, the joint patrols
are a flashpoint for tensions -- at a time when the two sides are
embarking on a high-stakes push to meet a Sept. 13 deadline for
reaching a final peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton announced Wednesday he had invited the two
sides to a summit next week at the Camp David presidential retreat,
but negotiators from both sides will have to overcome deep mistrust
to reach an accord. Reflecting that, the mood on the ground in the
Palestinian lands -- and within the joint patrols -- is angry and
volatile.
</P>
<P>
   Troops from both sides say physical confrontations are
commonplace during their patrols, carried out in orange-flagged
jeeps that are a familiar sight on the dusty backroads of the West
Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
   ''We beat the hell out of each other all the time,'' said the
commander of a four-man Israeli patrol as it made its rounds
through low sand dunes and scrubby brushland in central Gaza, with
a Palestinian jeep following closely behind.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't like the Israelis -- why should we?'' said a member of
the Palestinian patrol, a 19-year-old policeman named Mohammed. He
grew up in the squalid refugee camp of Khan Younis, not far from
where the jeeps were making their slow way along a roadway that
runs between a Palestinian village and a Jewish settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ''What happens almost every day is that there is some small
problem, some nonsense, and it turns into a big, big problem,''
said the Israeli patrol commander, a lieutenant in the paramilitary
border police who could only be identified by his first name, Ron.
''It's dangerous, and we know it, but we can't seem to stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   Only last week, he said, he said, his men came to blows with
their Palestinian counterparts. He did not want to say what set off
the clash, but there was first an exchange of ''unpleasant words,''
then shoving, then a fistfight -- and finally ''like this on both
sides,'' he said, making the chik-chuk sound of automatic rifles
being cocked.
</P>
<P>
   On this day's patrol, the Israeli and Palestinian commanders got
out of their jeeps and conferred at several points during an
hourlong drive in Gaza. During the stops, their men milled about,
the two groups staying apart.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides sometimes communicate in Hebrew, which many
Palestinian policemen learned while jailed in Israel during the
intefadeh, or uprising. Lt. Ron knows Arabic, though, and generally
speaks it with his counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   Such gestures don't stop pent-up anger from boiling over. When
Lt. Ron started work 18 months ago on the joint patrol, he was
newly discharged from the army and had just finished a combat stint
in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's hard to keep yourself under control if they point a
weapon at you -- you really have the impulse to shoot. It's
especially difficult for the younger guys,'' said the lieutenant,
who is 23.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli troops said Palestinian youngsters often lay in wait
for them, stoning their jeep once the Palestinian jeep had passed
by. The Palestinians, for their part, said they often encountered
hostility from Jewish settlers, which usually went unchallenged by
their Israeli patrol partners.
</P>
<P>
   The joint patrols were set up after the 1993 Oslo accords on the
theory that if the two sides had more day-to-day contact, their
acrimony might lessen. But both sides say they wonder whether
separation is a better option.
</P>
<P>
   ''The problem isn't just between the (patrol) teams, it's
between the Israeli and Palestinian people,'' said Jalal Subeh, a
Palestinian shift commander at the liaison office that coordinates
the patrols.
</P>
<P>
   ''I need a new job,'' Lt. Ron said tiredly. ''This one isn't
doing anyone any good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-05-00 1331 </TRAILER>
