<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sides Are Kept Apart in N. Ireland  </HEADLINE>
By SHAWN POGATCHNIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- With water cannons and a high
steel wall, British soldiers and police worked Wednesday to prevent
Protestants from breaching their lines and reaching a nearby
Catholic neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Protestant rioting sparked by the tense standoff in Portadown,
30 miles southwest of Belfast, has been spreading and intensifying
each night, particularly in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Orange Order, Northern Ireland's once-dominant
Protestant brotherhood, said they were determined to wear down
British security forces and force them to permit a parade Sunday
down Garvaghy Road, the main Catholic section of Portadown. They
denied responsibility for any violence.
</P>
<P>
   Orange supporters brought Belfast traffic to a standstill at
evening rush hour Wednesday, throwing human blockades across more
than a dozen key roads, stranding thousands of motorists.
</P>
<P>
   Catholics in isolated districts complained that the Royal Ulster
Constabulary, itself the primary target, wasn't doing enough to
protect them. Several Catholic families in north Belfast reported
having to evacuate their homes overnight when Protestants outside
shouted death threats and broke windows.
</P>
<P>
   ''The RUC have been tolerating road and street blocks being set
up. There have been Catholics evicted from their homes by mobs. All
of this raises the temperature,'' said Sinn Fein leader Gerry
Adams, whose Irish Republican Army-linked party has long campaigned
against the predominantly Protestant police force.
</P>
<P>
   But other politicians lauded police and army efforts,
particularly in Portadown, where nine officers were reported
wounded after being bombarded with gasoline bombs, firecrackers,
slingshot projectiles and even acid as they stood their ground at
the spot where Protestant marches have been blocked since 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''Petrol bombs, fireworks, ball bearings and acid squirted at
the police: Those are not the weapons of democrats or legitimate
protest. They are the weapons of the bully, and the bully will not
have his way,'' said Britain's minister for Northern Ireland, Peter
Mandelson.
</P>
<P>
   Mandelson said he supported the police's use of water cannons on
the Protestant crowd late Tuesday, a measure avoided since 1996. He
said he would back any security measure designed to get Northern
Ireland through its ''recurring nightmare'' of march-fueled
violence.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, army engineers adopted a previously used tactic --
a 20-foot-high steel wall across the Orangemen's intended marching
path.
</P>
<P>
   This week's substantial Protestant rebellion against British
authority reflects both immediate anger at being forced to concede
symbolic ground to Catholics and wider opposition to key sections
of Northern Ireland's 2-year-old peace accord that have taken shape
in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Good Friday pact proposed creating a joint
Protestant-Catholic administration that included four parties,
including Sinn Fein and Protestant hard-liners from the Democratic
Unionist Party.
</P>
<P>
   The unlikely coalition was formed in December and, after being
suspended when the IRA initially refused to make any disarmament
commitments, resumed power in May.
</P>
<P>
   But the Democratic Unionists on Wednesday renewed efforts to
bring the power-sharing experiment tumbling down again.
</P>
<P>
   Their two ministers within the 12-post Cabinet announced they
would resign from their positions July 27 in a bid to increase
pressure on the more pragmatic Protestant party in the coalition,
the Ulster Unionists.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Unionists said they would keep hold of their
posts by immediately nominating two new party activists as
ministers -- and daring other parties to accept or reject them.
</P>
<P>
   ''The gloves are off. We're taking no more nonsense from
anybody,'' said Democratic Unionist leader Ian Paisley.
</P>
<P>
   Paisley pledged to kill the Good Friday agreement by obstructing
government operations -- embarrassing Ulster Unionist leader David
Trimble, and building Protestant opposition to his
compromise-minded policies.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble and moderate Catholic politician Seamus Mallon, who
jointly oversee the Cabinet, condemned Paisley's latest maneuvers.
</P>
<P>
   ''How anyone can believe that rotating ministers regularly will
not harm the delivery of public services is a mystery,'' they said
in a joint statement. ''That is an abuse of the public interest and
a breach of the good faith which the two ministers pledged on
taking up office.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
