<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Kuwait Leader Has Lost Everything  </HEADLINE>
By DIANA ELIAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUWAIT (AP) -- For almost 10 years, Alaa Hussein's mother has
been regretting ever waking her eldest son that August morning so
that he help defend his country against invading Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
   The Kuwaiti reservist army officer was captured by Iraqis before
he even made it to a camp where Kuwaiti troops were assembling in
1990. He was picked to head a puppet ''interim Cabinet'' that was
disbanded less than a week later, when Baghdad annexed its small
neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1991 Gulf War forced Iraq out of Kuwait, Hussein was
in exile. A court in his homeland ruled him a traitor in 1993 and
sentenced him to death in absentia.
</P>
<P>
   His 57-year-old mother, Munira al-Humaidi, lifted her black
headdress to show a head bald but for a few white hairs. ''I lost
it all because of grief,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A court is to rule July 9 on an appeal by Hussein, after his
1993 conviction and death sentence were upheld in May.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein, who had been living in exile in Norway since 1998,
returned with his four children in January to contest the 1993 in
absentia conviction. He said he wanted to prove he had been forced
by Iraqi soldiers to take the puppet leadership post. Instead, the
court dismissed his arguments with its May ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have lost confidence in everything,'' the 41-year-old
Hussein told The Associated Press, joining a recent interview at
his sister's apartment through a phone call from prison.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now, I'm living among drug smugglers and killers who make fun
of me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein had broken down in tears when he spoke in court, trying
to explain that although his mother was Iraqi and he studied in a
Baghdad university before the 1990 invasion, he had no connections
to the ruling Baath Party.
</P>
<P>
   Public prosecutors have said Hussein could not produce any
evidence that he was forced to take the job.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein said the Iraqis would not let him leave Iraq after
Kuwait was liberated, though eight other members of the puppet
Cabinet, who were also Kuwaiti prisoners, were allowed to go home.
</P>
<P>
   Most of his fellow Cabinet members, who were cleared of any
wrongdoing upon their return, told the court they were not on good
terms with him in Iraq and he used to give them orders and threaten
them with death if they didn't comply. One said Hussein didn't show
any excitement when Iraq was driven from Kuwait, and seemed to
believe Iraq would win the Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein's children have been living with their grandparents,
aunts and uncles since their sudden return from Norway.
</P>
<P>
   ''We never thought they would do this to him. He is a war
prisoner not a traitor,'' said 14-year-old Saad. He said that in
Iraq and in Norway, his father was always sad and silent and
couldn't wait to come back to Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein's only daughter, Hoda, said she didn't want to go to
school in Kuwait, where she would have to hear other children
insulting her father.
</P>
<P>
   The teen-aged Hoda and her three brothers have asked to see the
emir, Sheik Jaber Al Ahmed Al Sabah, to ask for a pardon. It is
unlikely the ruler would consider the request before a final
verdict. Hussein has one other appeal beyond the court that is to
rule July 9.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein said he wanted Hoda, Saad, and the younger boys, Nawar,
7, and Mohammad, 10, to go back to Norway to live with their
stepmother. He married Sonya Shamoun, an Iraqi, after divorcing his
first wife in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have deprived my children of their father, they shouldn't
deprive them of their mother too,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-05-00 1416 </TRAILER>
