<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Discusses Iranian Jews  </HEADLINE>
By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- American Jewish leaders explored with
President Clinton on Wednesday how to pressure Iran to release 10
Jewish men sentenced to prison on espionage charges.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was an hourlong exploration of the facts; to talk about
possible pressure points,'' said Malcolm I. Hoenlein, executive
chairman of the Conference of Presidents of Major American Jewish
Organizations. ''The purpose was to declare to the world that the
United States is determined to bring about the release of these
innocent men.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not appear before reporters after the meeting.
Hoenlein said Clinton called the charges against the 10
Iranian-Jewish men unjust and the process used to convict them
unfair.
</P>
<P>
   Also attending the White House meeting were first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton, the Democratic candidate for the U.S. Senate in New
York, and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright,
</P>
<P>
   Family members of three of the 10 convicted Iranian-Jewish
prisoners also were present.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 were sentenced to prison terms ranging from four to 13
years; Hoenlein said there is concern that the prisoners will not
survive their sentences because of harsh prison conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ''The U.S. is the leader of the free world and does have some
moral persuasion'' to bring to bear, Hoenlein said. ''The president
is fully committed to doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's verdict drew condemnation from Israel, which denied
that the convicted men were spies, and from Clinton, who said he
was ''deeply disappointed'' that Iran appeared to have treated the
men unfairly.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 men were sentenced by an Iranian judge who acted as both
prosecutor and jury.
</P>
<P>
   Hoenlein said earlier in the week that he thought international
pressure may have helped avert death penalty sentences for the men
and could have a positive effect on the appeals process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
