<HEADLINE> Chinese Target Human Smugglers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- China's Fujian province has tightened border
controls in a bid to stop human smugglers, following the deaths of
58 Chinese illegal migrants during an attempt to reach Britain last
month, state media reported.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in coastal Fujian, where the smuggling trade is
based, have intensified their crackdown on the smugglers, known as
snakeheads, since the migrants were found dead in the back of a
truck in the British port of Dover, the government's Xinhua News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   It said the provincial government has tightened control on exit
applications and ''called for rapid development of the economy to
solve surplus labor and to improve people's living standard,'' the
report said. Stricter supervision of shipping and fishing vessels
off the Fujian coast has also been enforced, Xinhua said.
</P>
<P>
   But Xinhua added that the numbers of human smuggling cases
investigated so far this year are down from the first half of 1999,
despite a pair of three-month long crackdowns leading to the
arrests of 289 people on suspicion of organizing illegal passages.
</P>
<P>
   The report follows the visit to Fujian this week by Doris
Meissner, commissioner of the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization
Service, who said she hoped to improve communication and
cooperation between the United States and China in combatting
illegal migration. Prior to her visit, Meissner said in Beijing
that snakeheads were becoming increasingly sophisticated and had
largely abandoned crude methods of cramming would-be-migrants
aboard creaky vessels for the sea passage.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Fujian courts handled 296 cases involving illegal
migration. Ninety-seven people were sentenced to two years or more
in prison, Xinhua said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
