<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retail executive Alan Fortunoff dies at 67  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   	   OLD WESTBURY, N.Y. (AP) - Alan Fortunoff, president and CEO of
the Fortunoff retail chain, has died. He was 67.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunoff died in his sleep at his Old Westbury home on Tuesday
night of complications from cancer, said his spokesman, Gary Lewi.
</P>
<P>
   He started out sweeping floors and helping customers at his
family's housewares shop in Brooklyn. As customers began leaving
the city for the suburbs in the 1960s, the Fortunoffs moved their
store to Long Island, luring customers with a promise of ''everyday
low prices'' on goods ranging from diamonds and pearls to towels
and bathmats.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunoff built his family's company into a chain of popular
stores, opening outlets in New Jersey and on Fifth Avenue in
Manhattan. He helped create The Mall at The Source near his
Westbury store to draw shoppers to the area.
</P>
<P>
   ''Alan was committed to our future both as a corporate family
and as a retail leader,'' his family said in a statement. ''The
management depth and executive culture that he helped create will
not only sustain Fortunoff today but allow it to continue to grow
in the years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunoff, who earned a law degree at New York University, was a
trustee of the NYU Law Center Foundation and a member of the Dean's
Advisory Council at NYU's Stern School of Business. He helped fund
the Fortunoff Holocaust Archives at Yale University.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunoff is survived by his wife, Helene, four daughters and
two sons.
</P>
<P>
   A funeral is planned for 1 p.m. Thursday at Temple Sinai in
Roslyn Heights.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
