<HEADLINE> Lazio: Hillary Clinton has ''embarrassed our country''  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Republican candidate Rick Lazio, in a
fund-raising letter that came to light Wednesday, says his U.S.
Senate rival ''Hillary Clinton and her husband have embarrassed our
country and disgraced their powerful posts.''
</P>
<P>
   In his harshest attack to date on the first lady, the
congressman from Long Island writes that ''she covets power and
control and thinks she should be dictating how other people run
their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ''No other Senate hopeful enjoys a liberal national press that
hangs on her every word and treats her never-ending soap opera of
scandals as 'irrelevant' and 'yesterday's news,''' the four-page
letter adds.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate two-page letter coordinated with the Lazio
campaign, millionaire publisher Steve Forbes - whose former
political guru, Bill Dal Col, is now Lazio's campaign manager -
asks his former presidential campaign supporters to open their
checkbooks for the congressman.
</P>
<P>
   ''Deep down, Hillary knows that her wild-eyed radical leftist
views will repel the voters,'' Forbes writes. ''That's why she
engages in a predictable pattern of shameless hypocrisy, perpetual
pandering and cruel scapegoating against her opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   ''While she's a liberal extremist, Rick's a dyed-in-the-wool
conservative,'' Forbes adds, even though Lazio's campaign says the
candidate is a moderate. ''While she's ricocheted from one scandal
to another, Rick holds himself to the highest ethical standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the Lazio letter, Clinton campaign spokesman Howard
Wolfson said, ''We are confident that New Yorkers will reject Rick
Lazio's campaign of personal insults in favor of Hillary's campaign
of issue differences and real ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   During a more than 20-minute news conference aboard a campaign
bus in northern New York, Lazio acted as if he really wasn't
familiar with his own fund-raising letter. And, he said, ''That's
not part of our media campaign. That's not what I'm talking about
on the stump ... And frankly, these letters are written, you know,
not by me. I'm not disavowing it, but they're not written by me.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I just think that both Mrs. Clinton and the President have got
pretty significant liabilities that are well known by the public,''
Lazio added.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, declaring that Lazio's candidacy is the product of
''Republican Party kingmakers,'' the first lady was out with her
own direct-mail appeal asking for ''a special donation'' to keep up
her attacks on the congressman from Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our opponents understand how critical the next few weeks will
be in defining this contest. So do I,'' the first lady wrote in a
one-page appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, Clinton and her supporters launched six
television advertisements attacking Lazio's congressional record
and his stand on issues in an attempt to ''define'' Lazio for the
electorate before he has a chance to do that in a more positive
way.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio only entered the race on May 20 after Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani quit the contest, saying he had to deal with his newly
diagnosed prostate cancer. Lazio's substitute candidacy was quickly
endorsed by Gov. George Pataki and state GOP Chairman William
Powers, who effectively shut the door on other possible GOP
contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ''The vast right-wing conspiracy rides again,'' Lazio campaign
spokesman Dan McLagan said when asked about Clinton's letter. ''I
don't think even she believes this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   In her letter, Clinton reiterates her public theme that ''this
campaign is not about me or my opponent.'' She then quickly makes
it clear she thinks the race is about her and her opponent, or at
least where they stand on the issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''I support licensing and registration of handguns. He
doesn't,'' she writes. ''He has voted against the right to choose
(abortion) for low income women, even in cases of rape and incest.
I would never vote that way.''
</P>
<P>
   McLagan dismissed the letter as another example that the first
lady's ''campaign has been one of mudslinging distortions ... It's
sad, but not unexpected.''
</P>
<P>
   Defending Lazio's letter, McLagan said, ''There were never any
unanswered questions surrounding Barbara Bush. There are no
independent counsel reports on Rosalyn Carter. Under previous
administrations, the Lincoln Bedroom wasn't treated like Motel 6.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, who is in the midst of a five-day bus tour across the
state, has sent out several fund-raising letters in recent days.
One, addressed to ''Dear Fellow New Yorker,'' doesn't mention the
White House scandals associated with the Clinton administration. A
''Dear Friend'' letter does.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe elective office is a sacred trust that obligates us
to set the highest personal standards,'' Lazio writes in the
harsher of the two letters. ''She believes elective office is
something she deserves and is owed and should anyone question her
or her husband's integrity, she lashes out with ferocity at her
accusers.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Lazio had said the race would not be about Bill Clinton
or other politicians, but about he and the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ''This campaign for the United States Senate is not going to be
about Newt Gingrich and it's not going to be about Bill Clinton,''
he told ABC's ''This Week'' Sunday morning show on May 21.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Lazio letters actually made its way to Clinton
campaign headquarters in New York City, addressed to ''Bill
Rodham.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't have anybody here by that name,'' Clinton campaign
spokesman Howard Wolfson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-05-00 1535 </TRAILER>
