<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian tobacco lawsuit goes up in smoke in U.S. Court  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM KATES
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) - The Canadian government is considering
what course to take after a U.S. federal judge dismissed a novel $1
billion lawsuit alleging that R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co.
masterminded a booming smuggling trade to evade millions of dollars
in taxes.
</P>
<P>
   In a 55-page decision, U.S. District Judge Thomas McAvoy ruled
that Canada was treading on grounds where American courts had no
jurisdiction - at least under current law.
</P>
<P>
   McAvoy said the lawsuit ran afoul of an 18th-century English
common law rule adopted by the United States that prohibits its
courts from being used to collect another country's revenue. The
so-called ''Revenue Rule'' has been criticized as outdated in an
era of closely linked economies and tax treaties and McAvoy
suggested in his ruling that he would like to see a higher court
consider its validity.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a lengthy and complex ruling ... but the judge did not
address the factual merits of the case,'' said Gordon Bourgard, a
general counsel for the Canadian justice department. ''Obviously,
we are disappointed but his decision was based on a rule of law
that has been called into question by several courts.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourgard said on Wednesday that the Canadian government is
reviewing its options, which include appealing the decision in the
U.S. courts or pursuing the case in the Canadian judicial system.
</P>
<P>
   With great fanfare, the Canadian government filed its
unprecedented civil lawsuit in December in the United States, where
it could pursue triple damages under the federal Racketeering
Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act. Bourgard said the United
States' stronger mail and wire fraud statutes also prompted
Canada's decision to file the lawsuit in America.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit alleged that RJR and related companies set up an
elaborate network of smugglers and a shell company - Northern
Brands International - to flood Canada with cheap cigarettes after
the government doubled taxes and duties on tobacco in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   It further alleged that a Canadian subsidiary of Reynolds,
RJR-Macdonald Inc., used the Canadian Tobacco Manufacturing
Council, a trade group, to blame organized crime for the smuggling
while pretending it was trying to stop the activity.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said the ring smuggled $687 million worth of
cigarettes and alcohol into Canada from 1991 to 1997 through the
St. Regis Mohawk Reservation that straddles the border in northern
New York state.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two dozen people were convicted in connection with the
ring, including several prominent Mohawk businessmen, a former
tribal chief and a top tobacco executive with Northern Brands.
</P>
<P>
   RJR has steadfastly denied it played any role in encouraging the
smuggling ring.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are pleased that the federal court dismissed this case,
which should have never been brought in the first place,'' the
North Carolina-based tobacco company said in a statement issued
Wednesday. ''R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. hopes that the dismissal
will put an end to this matter once and for all.''
</P>
<P>
   In his decision issued Friday, McAvoy said Canada's lawsuit
would draw the U.S. court into ''forbidden waters reserved
exclusively to the legislative and executive branches'' of the U.S.
government that are responsible for establishing and conducting
international relations. The U.S. court would be required to pass
on the validity of, and enforce, Canadian revenue laws, the judge
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Enforcing foreign revenue laws is precisely the type of
meddling in foreign affairs the revenue rule forbids,'' McAvoy
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The case marked the first time a foreign government used the
civil provisions of the U.S. anti-racketeering law to target a
tobacco company for alleged cigarette smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Colombia followed in Canada's footsteps, filing a
$3-billion anti-racketeering suit in New York federal court against
the world's largest tobacco multinational, Philip Morris Companies
Inc., for lost tax revenue because of alleged smuggling and alleged
laundering of drug money.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Ecuador filed a lawsuit in federal court in Florida
against more than a dozen U.S. tobacco companies, including Philip
Morris and RJR, alleging they smuggled tobacco products in and out
of the South American country without paying duties and taxes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
