<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IRS Warns Charities, Churches  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Internal Revenue Service issued an
election-year warning Wednesday that churches, charities and many
other tax-exempt organizations should not engage in political
activities encouraging support for or opposition to any candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The organizations involved are exempt from federal income taxes
under section 501(c)(3) of the tax code.
</P>
<P>
   ''These organizations cannot endorse any candidates, make
donations to their campaigns, engage in fund raising, distribute
statements or become involved in any other activities that may be
beneficial or detrimental to any candidate,'' said the IRS
statement.
</P>
<P>
   The agency issued similar warnings prior to the 1992 and 1996
presidential elections; the warnings are not aimed at any
particular organization, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency said tax-exempt organizations could lose that status
or be subjected to an excise tax on the political money spent even
if they had no partisan motivation.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a federal appeals court upheld an IRS decision
denying tax-exempt status to the New York City bar association
because it published ratings of candidates for elective judicial
offices in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Contributions made to organizations that lose their 501(c)(3)
status are not deductible by the donors on their income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   IRS: http://www.irs.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
