<HEADLINE> Storied History for Camp David  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. president's Camp David retreat in
western Maryland is best known for the peace agreement reached
there between Egypt and Israel 22 years ago. Now, its rustic
setting offers a quiet venue for Israeli President Ehud Barak and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, hosted by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   President Franklin D. Roosevelt first used the hideaway in the
Catoctin Mountains during World War II. Much modernized, the
Navy-run camp 90 miles from Washington has been used by every
president since then for rest, recreation and as an informal place
to meet world leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The place has been Camp David since the 1950s when President
Eisenhower found Roosevelt's name, ''Shangri-La,'' a little fancy,
and renamed it for his 5-year-old grandson, David Eisenhower.
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt met there with Winston Churchill; Eisenhower with
Nikita Khrushchev; Richard Nixon with Leonid Brezhnev.
</P>
<P>
   The name gained international currency in September 1978 when
President Carter tirelessly brokered a cornerstone peace agreement
between Israeli Prime Minister Menachem Begin and Egyptian
President Anwar Sadat.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has not visited the retreat as often as his
predecessors, but has used it for diplomatic purposes before. The
first official dinner held for Barak was on the Camp David grounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
