<HEADLINE> Laudor committed to mental institution  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) - Michael Laudor, whose battle against
schizophrenia was once a Hollywood success story, was committed to
a mental institution Wednesday, two years after killing his
pregnant fiancee.
</P>
<P>
   State Supreme Court Justice Daniel Angiolillo ruled that Laudor,
37, ''has a dangerous mental disorder'' and should be sent to a
secure treatment center for the next six months. The order can be
extended for a longer term when his case is reviewed.
</P>
<P>
   In May, over the impassioned objections of the victim's family,
Laudor was found not responsible for the killing of Caroline
Costello, 37. She was found knifed to death on June 17, 1998, in
the kitchen of an apartment she shared with Laudor in
Hastings-on-Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   Three psychiatrists agreed that Laudor killed Costello because
he thought she was ''a nonhuman impostor'' conspiring to
hospitalize him for torture, experimentation and death. Prosecutors
were forced to concede that with the doctors' reports in evidence,
no jury would convict Laudor of murder.
</P>
<P>
   Laudor had graduated from - and even taught at - Yale Law School
despite his schizophrenia. He had sold book and movie rights to his
story and was considered a role model for victims who control
schizophrenia through medication.
</P>
<P>
   But after the death of his father in 1997, Laudor stopped taking
his medication, apparently believing it to be part of a conspiracy
against him. His condition worsened and his fiancee, his mother and
his doctor arranged a visit from a crisis intervention team. That
impending visit, according to one psychiatric report, precipitated
the killing because Laudor thought he would be tortured and
lobotomized.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, prosecutor Robert Prisco said reports from two
doctors at the Mid-Hudson Forensic Psychiatric Center in New
Hampton - where Laudor has spent the last two years - argued for
continued treatment. One said Laudor was ''dogged by symptoms''
even after being medicated. The other said Laudor ''continues to
receive messages through songs.''
</P>
<P>
   Laudor, unshaven and with his hands cuffed behind him, did not
speak. His attorney, Andrew Rubin, did not contest the commitment
order, but told the judge that Laudor had been nonviolent, and had
been taking his medication, since a few weeks after the killing.
</P>
<P>
   The drugs, which carry considerable side effects and can be
administered only gradually, were not yet at a therapeutic level
for Laudor, said Rubin, adding that his client's symptoms might
wane once that level is reached.
</P>
<P>
   Outside court, Laudor's brother Daniel said the commitment was
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all hope that care and medication will lead to whatever
improvements are possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the rules governing insanity pleas, if the state Office of
Mental Health and the court ever agree that Laudor is no longer a
danger to himself or others, he could eventually be released.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-05-00 1643 </TRAILER>
