<HEADLINE> US To Aid Honduran Victims  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hurricane victims in Honduras will move from
temporary to storm-resistant housing with help from $4.1 million in
U.S. aid, leaders of the two governments said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The assistance was announced in a joint statement by Housing
Secretary Andrew Cuomo and Honduran President Carlos Roberto
Flores.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Housing and Urban Development said the money
will help as many as 6,000 Honduran families move out of the
temporary housing they have used since Hurricane Mitch swept
through Central America in November 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the department said the aid will be help provide
long-term planning for building new and reconstructed communities;
rebuild damaged infrastructure; provide financing for home repairs;
and provide training in building houses designed to withstand
powerful storms.
</P>
<P>
   ''The assistance we're providing can speed up efforts to rebuild
communities, rebuild housing and create a better future,'' Cuomo
said
</P>
<P>
   Flores, speaking via satellite from Honduras, expressed
gratitude ''for the prompt and significant cooperation that the
United States extended during our emergency and for the subsequent
efforts of assistance and rehabilitation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
