<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge dismisses discrimination charges by former state police head  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A state Superior Court judge Wednesday
dismissed charges by the ousted head of the New Jersey State Police
that the governor wanted him to resign in retaliation for published
remarks he made linking minorities with drug trafficking and
discriminated against him because she wanted to appoint a younger,
black man.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman pressed for Superintendent Carl Williams
to resign in February 1999 after The Star-Ledger of Newark
published an interview in which he made comments about police
practicing racial profiling, or stopping motorists based on their
race.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman told Peter Verniero, who was attorney general at the
time, to call Williams at his Mount Laurel home and ask for his
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Williams filed a host of charges several months after he
resigned. Only two remain - allegations of defamation against
Assemblyman Leroy Jones Jr. and of libel against The Star-Ledger.
</P>
<P>
   Superior Court Judge Judith A. Yaskin on Wednesday dismissed
Williams' claims that he was retaliated against by the state and by
Whitman for his comments to the newspaper. The judge said, because
he resigned and was not fired, that did not constitute retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   She also dismissed charges that Whitman, Verniero and the state
discriminated against him, and that Whitman's spokesman, Peter
McDonough, defamed him.
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary Alito, the lawyer representing Whitman, McDonough and
the state, said that because Williams was a high-level political
appointee and he voluntarily resigned, his claim does not fall
under the protection of state or federal anti-discrimination laws.
</P>
<P>
   ''All of his claims that he was discriminated against because
he's white, because he's a man and because of his age were
dismissed,'' said Alito.
</P>
<P>
   The judge did give Williams 15 days to try to reassert a claim
that there was a conspiracy to defame him.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also dismissed Williams' claim that Verniero, as
attorney general, had a duty to advise him that he had a right to a
hearing and that he did not have to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Williams claimed that Verniero ''engaged in deceit or trickery
in order to get him to resign,'' said Wayne Positan, Verniero's
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   The judge dismissed those claims and said that Williams, as head
of the state police, could not ''justifiably claim that he didn't
know what his rights were,'' Positan said.
</P>
<P>
   On June 2, Yaskin dismissed Williams' attempt to collect $21
million in a personal injury lawsuit
</P>
<P>
   In September 1999, Whitman appointed Carson Dunbar Jr., a
47-year-old FBI special agent, to head the state police. Dunbar is
black.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' lawyer, Clifford Van Syoc, did not return a message
from The Associated Press on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's spokeswoman Jayne O'Connor said the governor had no
comment on the judge's decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-05-00 1700 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
