<HEADLINE> Six children thrown from pickup in crash; driver charged with DWI  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PERSIA, N.Y. (AP) - Six Buffalo children, ranging in age from
six to 12, were hurt in the crash of a pickup truck whose driver
was drunk, state police said.
</P>
<P>
   The children were thrown from the bed of the truck, which had a
cap, when the vehicle went off the shoulder of the road, hit a tree
and flipped in the Cattaraugus County Town of Persia, about 30
miles south of Buffalo Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the children, including the driver's 10-year-old son
and 12-year-old daughter, were listed in good condition Wednesday
at Children's Hospital in Buffalo. The others were treated at
Tri-County Hospital in Gowanda and released.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Bracero, 42, of Buffalo was arraigned in Persia Town Court
on charges of driving while intoxicated and endangering the welfare
of a child. Bracero, who also was ticketed for numerous traffic
violations, was being held in Cattaraugus County Jail in Little
Valley after failing to post $2,500 bail.
</P>
<P>
   State troopers said Bracero and the children were on their way
home from a picnic in the Zoar Valley state recreational area when
the crash occurred about 6:30 p.m. Several of the children's
parents were following in cars behind the pickup truck but it was
unclear whether they witnessed the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Bracero was scheduled to return to court July 11.
</P>
</TEXT>
