<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lieberman announces bid for third term  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) - U.S. Sen. Joseph Lieberman on Wednesday
announced his plans to seek re-election to a third term, touting
his work to clean up the entertainment industry and promising to
make education reform his top priority in the next six years.
</P>
<P>
   In a ceremony outside the Stamford house where he grew up and
surrounded by his mother, wife, sister, other relatives and
supporters, Lieberman said he had worked hard to promote family
values, reduce crime, reform the welfare system and strengthen
Connecticut's economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrat cited specifically his cosponsorship of the V-chip
law, which allows parents to control the television viewing of
their children, and charter schools legislation to expand
educational choices.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those are the responsibilities that the people of Connecticut
have entrusted in me. I have worked hard to uphold them, to realize
their common values and ideals, and I'm proud of the things we've
been able to accomplish together,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, 58, said if re-elected he would focus on federal
education reform, including giving local school systems more
flexibility in spending federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you educate poor kids better, they're going to find their
way up in America,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would also work to lower the cost of prescription
drugs, and to strengthen the long-term solvency of Medicare and
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, a former state senator and attorney general, stunned
Connecticut's political establishment in 1988 when he defeated
incumbent U.S. Sen. Lowell P. Weicker Jr. by 10,000 votes. Six
years later, he won the biggest landslide victory ever in a
Connecticut race for a U.S. Senate seat, a margin of more than
350,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months Lieberman has been mentioned as a possible
running mate for Vice President Al Gore. Lieberman said Wednesday
he is not seeking the job, but would consider it if asked.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't expect to be asked. Obviously, if that ever happened,
I'd certainly think about it, but to me, it's a nonevent.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's national profile was raised substantially in
September 1998 when he delivered a scathing speech on the Senate
floor accusing President Clinton - an old friend - of immoral
behavior in the Monica Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   Waterbury Mayor Philip Giordano, a Republican, last month
announced his challenge to Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano on Wednesday accused Lieberman of paying too much
attention to lobbyists who contribute to his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think Senator Lieberman has gotten too global. He's more
interested in raising his national profile than he is in actually
representing the state of Connecticut,'' said Giordano, 37, now in
his third term as mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's spokesman, Dan Gerstein, called Giordano's remarks,
''silly political games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-05-00 1711 </TRAILER>
