<HEADLINE> Business news in brief from around New Jersey  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MURRAY HILL, N.J. (AP) - Lucent Technologies Inc., the world's
largest telecommunications equipment maker, said Wednesday that it
has won an additional $570 million contract from San Diego,
Calif.-based Leap Wireless International Inc. for digital wireless
equipment and services.
</P>
<P>
   In September, Lucent received a $330 million award to build a
wireless phone network for one of Leap's fledging subsidiaries,
Cricket Communications. Cricket currently offers wireless service
in Tennessee and has obtained the rights to offer its service to
about 35 million potential customers throughout the United States.
</P>
<P>
   FAIRFIELD, N.J. (AP) - Prime Hospitality Corp. said Wednesday
that it has sold its Princeton Holiday Inn to Dallas-based
Remington Hotel Corp. for $18.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Prime has generated about $185 million from the sale of 16
hotels this year. The Fairfield-based company said the dispositions
are part of an effort to divest its real estate holdings and
concentrate on its franchise business.
</P>
<P>
   Prime owns or manages more than 200 hotels in the United States
and the U.S. Virgin Islands.
</P>
<P>
   PARSIPPANY, N.J. (AP) - DRS Technologies Inc. said Wednesday
that it has been awarded a multiyear contract to provide Canadian
Cormorant helicopters with flight-control computers.
</P>
<P>
   The contract, worth up to $14 million, was awarded by Smiths
Industries plc's aerospace group in Cheltenham, England.
</P>
<P>
   Under the contract, two DRS flight-control computers will be
installed on each helicopter. The Cormorant models are designed for
military and commercial maritime uses. It is frequently deployed
for anti-submarine warfare, search and rescue, casualty evacuation
and troop-transport missions.
</P>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The New Jersey State Police has awarded San
Diego, Calif.-based ImageWare Systems Inc. a contract to replace
the equipment used to take mug shots with a digital photography
system.
</P>
<P>
   ImageWare will be paid $203,300 to install its Crime Capture
System, a software package that will be used to create digital
arrest records for individuals being processed by the state police.
Once created, the images can be shared statewide over an existing
records-sharing network. The contract also includes three years of
service.
</P>
<P>
   ImageWare will also supply its Face ID software, which will
allow troopers to compare photos or composite images against their
database of arrest records to help identify unknown suspects and
individuals with multiple aliases.
</P>
<P>
   The system is expected to be operational in the fall, the
company said.
</P>
<P>
   PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) - Nex-i.com, a developer of network
infrastructures in multitenant commercial buildings, said Wednesday
it has named Jeff Pustay vice president of technology and
operations for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Pustay has more than 21 years in the information technology
industry. Before joining the company, he served as managing
director of technology for Navigant Consulting, a global consulting
firm.
</P>
<P>
   Pustay will become part of the Nex-i.com's management team that
is responsible for directing, administering and coordinating the
company's technology and network operations. He reports to
president and CEO Ira Baseman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
