<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Safir discusses park attacks with elected women officials  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Elected women officials said Wednesday that
Police Commissioner Howard Safir has promised to revise the patrol
guide to specifically talk about police behavior at large scale
events.
</P>
<P>
   If officers fail to take complaints from victims and follow up
on reports of criminal activities, the penalties will be severe,
Safir reportedly said at a closed-door meeting about last month's
Central Park attacks. Several officers there have been accused of
ignoring pleas for help from women who were either stripped, groped
or robbed by a roving band of young men.
</P>
<P>
   However, after the meeting with 22 women from Congress, the
state Assembly and city government, Safir said the group ''agreed
to nothing, except to work together.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir said he has been looking at making changes to the patrol
guide - the police ''bible'' of conduct - for some time.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we're going to define more specifically the
responsibilities of police officers at certain events so they're
codified and less ambiguous,'' Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   The women asked for the meeting to discuss why some officers
ignored crime victims in the park on June 11, following the Puerto
Rican Day Parade. The female public officials were outnumbered at
the meeting, held at Police Headquarters, by more than 50 police
officials, many of them women officers.
</P>
<P>
   The politicians expressed their gratitude for Safir meeting with
them. They were not pleased, however, with the NYPD's decision
against suspending five officers and six commanders in connection
with the Central Park attacks.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Safir released the first phase of the NYPD's internal
investigation into police behavior at the park.
</P>
<P>
   Four commanders received letters of reprimand. Two commanders
received ''letters of instruction'' spelling out what went wrong
after the Puerto Rican Day parade and how not to repeat the
mistakes. Five officers and three civilian 911 dispatchers face
still unspecified discipline procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel that everyday that there is a lack of an appropriate
response from the police department is really an insult to every
resident here in our city,'' said Rep. Carolyn Maloney,
D-Manhattan. She wrote a letter last month to Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani asking for a meeting; the mayor asked Safir to conduct it.
</P>
<P>
   The group also said that 24 of the 59 victims have alleged that
the officers they approached for help ignored them. Safir has said
only six victims accused officers of ignoring them.
</P>
<P>
   Of the officers named in the internal investigation, two were
cited for ignoring three victims. Safir has said the investigation
is ongoing, and more officers could be disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilwoman Christine Quinn did acknowledge that the NYPD
is still talking with victims. Some are being brought back to the
park and asked if they can remember where they approached officers
for help. The department then tries to pinpoint which officers were
assigned to those locations.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some changes are in the works.
</P>
<P>
   The public officials who met with Safir said he promised to
equip all police officers at large events with radios in the
future. Only sergeants had them at the Puerto Rican Day Parade.
</P>
<P>
   The department will also put one supervisor in charge of big
events. The internal police report on the June 11th problems points
out that many of the park attacks occurred along Central Park
South, the border of two NYPD commands.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the public officials who met with Safir called the
meeting conciliatory, City Councilwoman Annette Robinson called the
gathering an ''opening salvo.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-05-00 1721 </TRAILER>
