<BODY>
<HEADLINE> An analysis of NARAL's ad questioning Lazio on abortion  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   An analysis of the National Abortion and Reproductive
Rights
Action League's ad questioning Republican Senate candidate Rick
Lazio's position on abortion:
<TEXT>
<P>
   TITLE: ''One Question.''
</P>
<P>
   LENGTH: 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: Democratic political consultant Hank Sheinkopf.
</P>
<P>
   AIRING: Cable markets, primarily Long Island and Westchester but
with some distribution in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   SCRIPT: (On-screen announcer) I have one question for Rick
Lazio. How would he vote in the United States Senate when it comes
to the Supreme Court and abortion?
</P>
<P>
   Like most New Yorkers, I believe it's a woman's right to decide.
</P>
<P>
   One Supreme Court decision could rob us of this choice.
</P>
<P>
   Now Rick Lazio is saying he can't promise New Yorkers he'd
oppose anti-choice judges.
</P>
<P>
   So how would Rick Lazio vote on Supreme Court nominations?
</P>
<P>
   It's a simple question. New Yorkers deserve an answer.
</P>
<P>
   IMAGES: The advertisement is narrated by a woman seated in a
living room.
</P>
<P>
   Her voice is heard throughout the ad, but her image is replaced
by the words ''How would Lazio vote?'' followed by footage of
Robert Bork's Supreme Court hearings and a headline about Lazio
from the New York Post that reads: ''Pro-choice GOP candidate is a
master of ambiguity.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Will Lazio Oppose Anti-Choice Judges?'' then appears on the
screen, followed by ''For More Information About Lazio's
Anti-Choice Voting Record, Call 1-877-NARALNY.''
</P>
<P>
   ANALYSIS: This ad is designed to appeal to suburban women who
are independent voters, age 35 to 45, who strongly favor abortion
rights. The narrator, Ross DeMarco, who is not identified in the
ad, is not a professional actress but a NARAL member who lives on
Long Island. NARAL director Kelli Conlon said she was chosen
because ''we wanted to have a face that represented'' the voters
they are trying to reach.
</P>
<P>
   Conlin said the ad includes a reference to Bork because he is
''the quintessential example'' of a Supreme Court nominee who
acknowledged opposing Roe v. Wade. ''We need to know if there's
another Bork nominated, our senator will vote against that,'' she
said. Bork was nominated to the Supreme Court by President Reagan
in 1987 but rejected by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The ad was paid for and created by NARAL, which has endorsed
Hillary Rodham Clinton in the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has said repeatedly that she would only back Supreme
Court nominees who support Roe v. Wade.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, campaigning upstate Wednesday, described himself as
pro-choice but reiterated his refusal to prejudge any candidate for
the high court. ''I just don't think there ought to be a litmus
test,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, he told the New York Post he would take court
nominees' abortion views into consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ''You want to have as much information as you possibly can about
a judge's philosophical proclivities and where they're headed and
how they got there ... I want to know how they are reasoning on the
issue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has voted against Medicaid funding for abortion, against
allowing privately-funded abortions at overseas military hospitals
except in cases of rape or incest, and opposes the late-term
abortions called ''partial-birth'' by critics.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Analysis by Beth J. Harpaz, Associated Press writer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-05-00 1738 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000705.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State recommends ways to prevent and investigate computer crime  </HEADLINE>
By J.J. THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The state needs to update its computer
crime laws, coordinate law enforcement and educate the public to
keep up with increasingly sophisticated computer criminals,
according to a report released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The State Commission of Investigation and the Attorney General's
Office recommended ways New Jersey can prevent and investigate
computer crimes such as hacking, personal identity theft and child
sexual abuse.
</P>
<P>
   A good first step, according to the report, would be to update
the state's computer crime law, which was enacted in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The report noted that the law was so outdated that it failed to
recognize advances in technology such as the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been 16 years since it was updated and it hasn't been
used in years,'' said Robert Clark, commission deputy director.
</P>
<P>
   Police and prosecutors also need to designate someone in every
department or office who is responsible for dealing with computer
crimes, Clark said. They should decide if they need to dedicate
special investigative units to computer crime, which would then
coordinate efforts with the Attorney General's Office.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators need to work closely with the federal government
and private sector, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''All of this is so that the state can be on the cutting edge
when it comes to (investigating) computer criminals,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   The Attorney General's Office continues to work on training and
coordinating enforcement through its Internet Working Group, said
spokesman Paul Loriquet. It's now up to the Legislature to act on
recommended changes to computer crime laws.
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel we made a good presentation (in the report),'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other recommendations included maintaining the prohibition on
Internet gambling and establishing toll-free hot lines for computer
crime complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The commission heard three days of expert testimony on computer
crime in 1999. It topped off an investigation by the commission and
the Attorney General's Office.
</P>
<P>
   The 150-page report details a wide range of issues such as
Internet fraud, gambling and hate crimes. Pornography and
pedophiles who stalk the Internet were an area of major concern.
</P>
<P>
   During the hearings, experts testified that online child
pornography and pedophiles pose a much larger risk than most
parents and teachers realize.
</P>
<P>
   Pedophiles meet children through Internet chat rooms or e-mail,
and pornography rings use it to transmit porn.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a mother of three small children, I was particularly
shocked at the extent to which the Internet has become a means for
the abuse and exploitation of children,'' SCI Commissioner Audriann
Kernan stated in a press release.
</P>
<P>
   To combat the problem at home, the report suggests parents
monitor what their children are looking at on the Internet,
preferably by keeping the computer in a busy room such as the
kitchen or den. Installing blocking or filtering software to
prevent children from certain sites also is recommended.
</P>
<P>
   In school it's important for teachers and librarians to
supervise students using the Internet and provide tips for avoiding
sexual predators online, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-05-00 1741 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000705.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Concerned With Iraqi Activity  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP)-- The State Department expressed concern
Wednesday about actions at Iraqi sites that it said are known to be
capable producing weapons of mass destruction and long range
ballistic missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Another concern, the department said, is Iraq's
''long-established practice'' of acquiring materials that have
civilian uses but also could be used to make powerful weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The department commented in a written response to press
questions about a New York Times story last Saturday that said Iraq
has restarted its missile program and has conducted flight tests of
a short-range ballistic missile.
</P>
<P>
   The tests -- eight since as early as May 1999, including one last
week -- have involved Al Sambaed, a liquid-fueled ballistic missile
that could carry conventional explosives or the chemical and
biological weapons that Iraq is still suspected of hiding,
according to Clinton administration and military officials cited by
the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department response said that in the absence of United
Nations inspectors on the ground in Iraq, uncertainties about the
significance of these activities will persist.
</P>
<P>
   ''As time passes our concerns will increase,'' it said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
