<HEADLINE> Ex-military academy employee pleads guilty to arranging tryst with 'boy' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A longtime employee of a prestigious
Pennsylvania military academy pleaded guilty Wednesday to crossing
state lines to have sex with a minor.
</P>
<P>
   Computer specialist James P. Hopkinson Jr., 50, had worked at
Valley Forge Military Academy and College in Wayne, Pa., for 25
years before resigning last year.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkinson lived on the campus of the all-male school, which has
about 800 students ranging in age from 12 to 21, but school
officials have said he had no improper contact with any of them.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkinson was arrested April 21, 1999, at a northern New Jersey
mall, where he had gone to meet a 14-year-old boy he'd met on the
Internet a week earlier. The teen was actually an undercover FBI
agent who met Hopkinson in a chat room where adults have been known
to seek juveniles for sex.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Donna A. Krappa said Hopkinson pleaded
guilty before U.S. District Court Judge Garrett E. Brown Jr. to a
charge of traveling interstate to engage in a sexual act with a
minor.
</P>
<P>
   He faces up to 15 years in prison and a $250,000 fine when
sentenced on Sept. 25, but under federal guidelines the sentence
would be less severe.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkinson also pleaded guilty to a charge filed in Pennsylvania
of possession of child pornography. Krappa said authorities
searched Hopkinson's home on the day he traveled to New Jersey and
found magazines that contained child pornography.
</P>
<P>
   On that charge, he faces up to five years in prison and a
$250,000 fine, Krappa said.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkinson agreed to forfeit his home computer, which was taken
during the search.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkinson had been sentenced to home detention with electronic
monitoring. On Dec. 31, 1999, he had been given permission to do
some errands, Krappa said. His probation officer was notified that
day that his electronic bracelet had been deactivated. Hopkinson
was found at Jefferson Hospital in Philadelphia after an apparent
suicide attempt, Krappa said.
</P>
<P>
   He was released from the hospital on Jan. 13 and ordered to
undergo psychological testing. Hopkinson was then held at the
Monmouth County Jail, Krappa said.
</P>
<P>
   Hopkinson resigned from the school about a week before his
arrest because he was unhappy with changes in his job duties within
the school's information systems department, said school
spokeswoman Heather Swech.
</P>
<P>
   The school, which was founded in 1928, is the alma mater of such
people as Gen. H. Norman Schwarzkopf and author J.D. Salinger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
