<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leaving behind swords and buttons, Italian navy cadets fish for love </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Fresh off the tall ship Amerigo Vespucci and on
his first visit to New York, Italian navy cadet Giacomo Persi-Paoli
had no trouble finding his way around. Within a day, he and his
buddies had dates lined up with five American women.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have girlfriends back home. But we will be faithful,''
promised Persi-Paoli, 21, who kicked off his 15-hour shore leave on
Wednesday by shopping for athletic shoes and CDs.
</P>
<P>
   At 7 p.m., he and four other sailors were going dancing with
women they met Tuesday night at a Union Square restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Conclusion: ''New Yorkers are much friendlier than Italians,''
said Persi-Paoli, a native of Livorno, Italy, where the country's
elite naval academy is based.
</P>
<P>
   His girlfriend had one thing going for her: Her beau was due
back in his hammock by 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Each in their first year of training, the 21-year-olds stepped
out in Manhattan in dark blue, hand-sewn jackets and perfectly
tailored snow white pants. The sailors wandered around the city
without the ceremonial gold-and-pearl swords they usually carry on
their sides. ''They told us it was too dangerous to wear them in
New York,'' said cadet Gianpaolo Misseritti.
</P>
<P>
   Also left behind were spare buttons for their uniform jackets,
which have a ring of gold buttons around each sleeve - with one
missing.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a tradition, from the time when a member of the Italian
royal family, a cadet, fell in love and ripped a gold button off
his sleeve to leave to the woman,'' said Alessandro Crocetta.
</P>
<P>
   He was among 120 cadets from the 331-foot frigate Amerigo
Vespucci, discovering the land named after the Florentine navigator
whose name the vessel bears.
</P>
<P>
   ''Until now, our only steps off the ship were to carry off the
garbage,'' Crocetta said as he saluted the Italian flag and left
Pier 86 on the West Side.
</P>
<P>
   His group wanted to see a part of the city few New Yorkers ever
heard of: ''Brocolino,'' said Carlo Corso. That's Brooklyn, as old
Italian immigrants called it.
</P>
<P>
   But first, Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is just like the movies! There's life, there's always
movement!'' said Corso, his Italian singing with excitement as he
walked a seedy stretch of 42nd Street, eyes meeting the
skyscrapers. ''Even the ugly areas are fascinating. And look at
these cars - they're bigger, more elegant than the Italian ones.
This is the New World!''
</P>
<P>
   And there was another bit of Americana to bite into: ''Ot
dohgs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Hot dogs, of course.)
</P>
<P>
   They had no interest in pizza. After all, the baker aboard their
ship made ''midnight pizza'' - gourmet pies made from scratch every
night and delivered to those on duty until 4 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   On the pier, U.S. Navy staffers were passing out a ''hangout
guide,'' including entertainment tips and a map of the New York
subway system.
</P>
<P>
   It was an item two ordinary sailors from the Vespucci failed to
pick up.
</P>
<P>
   Standing confused in the middle of bustling Times Square, they
caught sight of their fellow mariners and asked for help getting to
Greenwich Village.
</P>
<P>
   Sailor Giacomo Magrone was in New York for the first time, too,
and was getting a tattoo at a Bleecker Street address a friend
recommended.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want anything tribal, or ugly. Maybe just a dragon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
