<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Farmers Fret Over Economy  </HEADLINE>
By ANGUS SHAW
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- White farmers warned Wednesday of
economic collapse if Zimbabwe does not take urgent action to end
the seizures of white farms and restore order.
</P>
<P>
   Rural violence has already destroyed a fifth of the Zimbabwe's
tobacco crop, on which it relies for export earnings, said Tim
Henwood, head of the Commercial Farmers Union. Militants have also
disrupted normal farming operations, slaughtered cattle and scared
off foreign investors, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that if the militants are not stopped, the entire sector
could breakdown, which analysts said could cost tens of thousands
of jobs and trigger a financial crisis as farmers default on loans
owed to banks.
</P>
<P>
   ''Farmers are unable to plan ahead and are not investing in
their farms. The situation is simply no longer tenable,'' said
Henwood, whose union represents about 4,000 white farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last five months, militants have occupied more than
1,600 white-owned farms, and threats against white farmers continue
unabated, the union said. Violence has claimed the lives of 31
people, including five white farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The occupations began after President Robert Mugabe lost a
constitutional referendum in February that would have empowered him
to seize white-owned farms for the resettlement of landless blacks
without paying compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Militant supporters in the countryside, many of whom fought
under Mugabe's command in Zimbabwe's war of independence in 1980,
took matters into their own hands, seizing land they say was
unlawfully taken by white settlers from its original black
inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe calls the wave of seizures ''a minor trespass''
protesting unfair ownership of land by whites and ordered police
not to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   Independent economist John Robertson said the farmers were
correct in warning the lawlessness and seizures threaten to plunge
the economy deeper into crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks could force farmers to default on the some $160
million that they owe banks, and wipe out jobs not only in
agriculture but in industries that depend on agricultural products,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a very serious risk of civil unrest from the ordinary
employee who has lost his job and cannot feed his family. It's not
that food won't be available, he won't have the money to buy it,''
Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture accounts for 18 percent of Zimbabwe's gross domestic
product, and commercial farms such as those owned by white farmers
earn about two-fifths of the nation's hard currency, according to
official figures.
</P>
<P>
   Hard currency shortages have already caused acute gasoline and
power shortages, Henwood said, and ''the prognosis ... is worsening
by the day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
