<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Charter plane crash investigation yields few answers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) - There are indications that at least one of the
engines on a doomed charter plane may have been operating just
before it crashed in the Pocono Mountains in May, federal crash
investigators reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The crash killed all 19 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the engines were functioning at the time of impact was
an immediate focus of the investigation by National Transportation
Safety Board officials. A statement from the agency Wednesday said
a careful study of the engines revealed the right engine propeller
may have been turning, but noted that whether the engine actually
had power has not been confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Flight times for the plane and fuel burn rates are also being
studied to determine if the plane may have run out of gas.
</P>
<P>
   Officials believe they have a general outline of what happened
just before the Executive Airlines twin-engine turboprop crashed in
the rain nine miles south of the Wilkes-Barre/Scranton
International Airport on May 21. The plane was returning passengers
from the Scranton/Wilkes-Barre area who had been on a casino junket
to Atlantic City, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots declared an emergency soon after missing their first
approach of an airport runway, according to investigators. Just
before the second approach, the pilots said they had lost both
engines.
</P>
<P>
   Air traffic controllers began providing information about the
terrain and elevation after radar indicated the plane was flying at
about 2,000 feet above sea level, considerably lower than the
minimum safe altitude, officials said. The crash site was 1,765
feet above sea level.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: National Transportation Safety Board:
http://www.ntsb.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
