<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin Makes Trip for Chechnya Talks  </HEADLINE>
By YURI BAGROV
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZRAN, Russia (AP) -- President Vladimir Putin blamed poor
military discipline for heavy Russian losses in suicide truck
bombings in Chechnya, rebuking top officials during a surprise
visit Wednesday to the volatile region.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's appearance in neighboring North Ossetia came amid tight
security and high tensions in and around Chechnya, prompted by the
Sunday night bombings.
</P>
<P>
   The five truck bombings killed at least 33 soldiers and wounded
scores of people and posed the biggest setback in months to Russian
forces trying to re-establish control over the rebel republic.
</P>
<P>
   ''Large losses could have been avoided. For that, strict
discipline, professionalism and responsibility is needed,'' Putin
told a meeting at military headquarters in the city of Mozdok,
according to Russian news agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting included Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev, Interior
Minister Vladimir Rushailo, top commanders, and the Chechen head of
the pro-Moscow administration in the republic, Akhmad Kadyrov, the
Kremlin press service said.
</P>
<P>
   Sergeyev and other Russian officials had also blamed the suicide
bombings on a lack of discipline among troops, including heavy
drinking and bribe-taking. The truck drivers made it past military
checkpoints and into cities the Russians claim to control.
</P>
<P>
   While in Mozdok after leaving a summit in Tajikistan, Putin
ordered government bodies in Chechnya to obey the defense
minister's commands, Interfax said. He told interior minister
Rushailo to speed up formation of police units consisting of loyal
Chechens, saying the local population can better determine who the
rebels are.
</P>
<P>
   Putin owes some of his popularity among Russians to his firm
handling of the Chechnya war and hawkish dismissal of international
criticism of the offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bombings, he said, the rebels have been reduced to
tactics of ''sneaking out of corners ... An end will be put to
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian forces have been saying for weeks that organized
resistance has been wiped out -- yet the rebels have inflicted
steady casualties with ambushes and hit-and-run attacks in areas
the Russians claim to control.
</P>
<P>
   ''At present the Russian military are confident that the war is
coming to an end, but we believe that it's the end of war for them,
whereas our war has just begun,'' rebel commander Khamzat Gelayev
told The Associated Press on Wednesday from a base in Chechnya's
southern mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have always lacked food and weapons, but had we had enough
of each we would have been in Moscow by now,'' Gelayev claimed.
</P>
<P>
   Federal troops took control of the northern two-thirds of
Chechnya early in the 10-month-old war, but have been chasing rebel
bands in the rugged terrain in the south for months.
</P>
<P>
   The coffins of members of a police detachment from Chelyabinsk,
in the Urals Mountains, were returned home Wednesday by plane, and
local officials declared a day of mourning. Twenty-two of those
killed in the bombings came from the Chelyabinsk region.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops rolled into Chechnya in September to restore
federal control over the rebellious region. Russian troops were
driven out by independence fighters in a 1994-96 war, but went back
in after Islamic militants based in Chechnya raided villages in
Dagestan, and after about 300 people died in apartment bombings the
government blames on Chechens.
</P>
<P>
   Putin praised the overall campaign Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Few could have imagined that after the invasions of Dagestan,
the actions of the federal organs would be so decisive, and the
results so fundamental,'' he said, according to Interfax.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-05-00 1959 </TRAILER>
