<HEADLINE> Armstrong Takes Front-Office Post  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Recently retired guard B.J. Armstrong rejoined
the Chicago Bulls on Wednesday as a special assistant to team
general manager Jerry Krause.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, an 11-year NBA veteran, retired at the end of last
season. He will replace Clarence Gaines Jr., who has left the team
to pursue other career opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Krause said Armstrong would handle a ''wide variety of scouting
assignments'' and would be involved in ''all aspects'' of scouting
and player development.
</P>
<P>
   ''As a player, I developed great respect for the way the Bulls
organization operates,'' Armstrong said. ''I have a great
opportunity to learn the other end of professional basketball from
the best in the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong, 33, started and ended his career in Chicago in two
stints with the team that included the Bulls' first three
championship seasons in 1991-1993. He played in 27 games last
season, averaging 7.4 points and 2.9 assists.
</P>
