<HEADLINE> Astros Release Reliever  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- Veteran reliever Mike Maddux was released
unconditionally by the Houston Astros on Wednesday after an
injury-plagued season in which he went 2-2 with a 6.26 ERA in 21
games.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Wade Miller was recalled from Triple-A New Orleans
to replace Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux missed 29 games with a strained groin from May 21 to June
22. In three games since, he allowed five runs on seven hits and
three walks over just 4 1-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The brother of Atlanta Braves ace Greg Maddux signed a minor
league contract with the Astros last January and won a spot on the
roster in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Miller was 4-5 with a 3.67 ERA and 81 strikeouts in 105 1-3
innings in New Orleans. He made his major league debut last season,
when he pitched in five games with an 0-1 record and 9.58 ERA in
September.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros announced their intention to put Miller into the
starting rotation and send Octavio Dotel, 1-5 with a 5.77 ERA, at
least temporarily to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Miller is expected to make his first start Saturday against the
Kansas City Royals.
</P>
