<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inmate restrained with stun gun before death  </HEADLINE>
sywvitnews12fons
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) - A Connecticut inmate who died in a
maximum-security Virginia prison was probably going into insulin
shock when he was restrained for a behavior problem, the prisoner's
family said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence James Frazier, 50, lapsed into a coma just hours after
he was restrained with a stun gun at Wallens Ridge State Prison in
Big Stone Gap, Va. He died on Tuesday of apparent heart failure,
correction officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier was the second Connecticut inmate to die this year at
Wallens Ridge, where nearly 500 state prisoners have been
transferred because of overcrowding.
</P>
<P>
   ''My brother was murdered,'' Thomas Frazier said in a news
conference Wednesday. He said his brother was a diabetic who
suffered from high blood pressure and often complained of not
getting his medication since his transfer to Wallens Ridge in
December.
</P>
<P>
   Department of Correction spokesman Scott Semple said he could
not comment on Frazier's medical history, but inmates with serious
medical conditions are not transferred and Frazier met the
criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers critical of the state's decision to send inmates to
Wallens Ridge say prisoners and their families have complained of
inadequate medical attention.
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy has been conducted, but correction officials said
results are still pending.
</P>
<P>
   Correction officials were investigating whether the use of force
was appropriate. The agency said it was important to keep in mind
that Frazier, who was serving a 30-60 year sentence for multiple
counts of sexual assault, had 103 disciplinary reports. Frazier was
convicted of repeatedly raping a woman during a robbery in her
Westport home in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier, formerly of Bridgeport, had been taken to the prison's
medical unit on June 29 for a health problem unspecified by
correction officials. When he was cleared by a doctor to return to
his cell, he became unruly and was restrained in a medical cell
with an electronic controlling device, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Frazier was found unresponsive later that day and taken to a
hospital. He remained on life support until he died early Tuesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   The state has come under fire for transferring inmates to
Wallens Ridge. The state Commission on Human Rights and
Opportunities is investigating allegations that the overwhelmingly
white prison staff has hurled racial insults at Connecticut
inmates, beat them and denied access to lawyers and religious
services.
</P>
<P>
   In April, David Tracy, a 20-year-old inmate from Bridgeport,
hanged himself in his cell at Wallens Ridge. A month earlier, three
Connecticut inmates were shot with rubber bullets by guards trying
to break up a scuffle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-05-00 2041 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000705.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Juror Deliberations Drag On  </HEADLINE>
By SUZANNE GAMBOA
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO (AP) - Jurors ended another day of deliberations
without a verdict Wednesday in the trial of Allen Blackthorne, a
millionaire accused of plotting the grisly death of his ex-wife.
</P>
<P>
   Following a holiday break, jurors returned to consider whether
Blackthorne hired golfing buddy Daniel Rocha to arrange the murder
of Sheila Bellush.
</P>
<P>
   The panel had deliberated part of Thursday and on Friday and
Monday before pausing for the Fourth of July. They deliberated
about 10 hours on Wednesday before quitting for the evening. They
were to resume at 9 a.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony lasted about three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Bellush was killed on Nov. 7, 1997, about two months after
moving with her second husband, Jamie Bellush, and six children to
Sarasota, Fla. She had been beaten and shot and her throat
slashed.The quadruplets from Bellush's second marriage were
discovered unharmed in the house, two of them crawling in their
mother's blood. Jamie Bellush and the children now live in Sussex
County, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Blackthorne, 45, is charged with interstate conspiracy to commit
murder-for-hire and with interstate domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   As of Wednesday afternoon, jurors had sent more than a dozen
notes to U.S. District Judge Edward Prado, some dealing with juror
business such as adjournment times and others relating to questions
about the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Requests for a transcript of testimony were rejected and jurors
were told to rely on their memory. Also refused was a request for
evidence that was referred to in the trial but was not part of the
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, jurors wanted to know the rules concerning what
evidence lawyers must provide opposing counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ''Does the defense have to give the prosecution all the evidence
they have?'' the jurors asked.
</P>
<P>
   Prado responded that the issue was a court matter.
</P>
<P>
   ''You are to consider only the evidence before you,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors allege that Blackthorne asked Rocha to find a hit
man to bludgeon Bellush. Rocha testified he contacted his friend,
Sammy Gonzales, who hired his cousin, Jose Luis Del Toro, the
alleged gunman.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gonzales and Rocha are serving prison terms in Florida for
solicitation of murder.
</P>
<P>
   Del Toro, 23, is scheduled for trial next month in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   With deliberations dragging on, the third floor of the federal
courthouse has become a waiting room for the trial regulars,
family, friends and witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   A group of regulars sat in a line with family members outside
the third floor courtroom that at times has had overflow crowds.
Several said they have decided what the verdict should be, but they
declined to share their opinion on the record.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel that this case here is an unusual case,'' said Sandy
Gruenewaldt, a retired civil service worker, ''and it's common
knowledge who's guilty and who's not.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys in the case have agreed not to talk to media before a
verdict is returned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-05-00 2048 </TRAILER>
