<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attorneys Blow Whistle on Agency  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHER NEWTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) -- Barbers and dentists across Pennsylvania
called them ''the terror team'' -- state prosecutors who handed out
scores of fines for occupational-license violations with
uncompromising efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   A barber who gave a quick trim to a customer on the back porch
of his barber shop was slapped with a $150 fine. A barber who let
Girl Scouts wash cars in his parking lot was fined $250.
</P>
<P>
   Now two of the team's lead attorneys have switched sides and are
suing the state of Pennsylvania, alleging they were forced to
prosecute trivial matters so that the agency could justify its
existence and its expanding budget.
</P>
<P>
   In their lawsuits, they allege what many critics already believe
-- the agency had a quota and picked on small businesses that
couldn't fight back.
</P>
<P>
   ''This system has become a monster, and it is so clearly illegal
that it should make any lawyer sick,'' said former state Auditor
Don Bailey, who is representing attorney Jeffrey Brown in his
lawsuit against the state's Bureau of Professional and Occupational
Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is common knowledge that a quota system is unconstitutional
-- and these were lawyers that were doing this! They systematically
went after people who were easy pickings and took advantage of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bureau spokesman Bob Bunty denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ''No quota system exists,'' he said. ''There were performance
goals for various bureau employees, but there were no admonishments
or punishments and no rewards for exceeding those goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Bunty would not comment on the purpose of the goal system.
</P>
<P>
   News of the lawsuit sent cheers through some barber shops that
have received fines in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ''Great! What goes around finally came around,'' said Joe
Gardner, who cuts hair at B.D.'s Barber Shop in Harrisburg. He said
his shop was fined $150 two years ago because there was ''too much
hair on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This has been unfair for years and so I'm not surprised to
hear about this,'' he said. ''You always knew they were just
looking for a reason to slap a fine on you.''
</P>
<P>
   The bureau licenses and regulates numerous professionals,
including doctors, dentists, nurses, accountants, architects,
cosmetologists, barbers and funeral directors. Agency workers
conduct inspections, and state attorneys hand out fines for
violations.
</P>
<P>
   Fines can be disputed, ''but doing so can be more costly than
paying the fine,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   In the lawsuit, filed Monday in federal court, Brown said
managers three years ago started pressuring attorneys to bring in
''bigger numbers'' and actually discussed how many fines they
expected attorneys to hand out.
</P>
<P>
   And more important, Brown said ''the quota system curtailed
prosecution of major illegal activity since these prosecutions were
deemed by supervisors to produce too few numbers of convictions in
relation to the amount of time needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown and co-worker Karen Grigsby said they were fired when they
complained of the system. The bureau would not comment on why they
were fired.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's suit names as defendants the entire management staff of
the licensing agency and a federal judge who allegedly knew about
the system and allowed the fines to continue. The defendants
declined to comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-05-00 2129 </TRAILER>
