<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Challenges Drug Industry Group  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE GLOVER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore criticized ''phony''
critics of his health proposals Wednesday, saying big drug
companies are plowing millions of dollars into a group that runs
ads against him rather than into research.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spoke to a convention of the American Federation of
Teachers, but focused more on health care than education. His
strongest fire was aimed at those critical of his plan to expand
Medicare to cover prescription drug costs.
</P>
<P>
   He released a letter in which he had demanded that Citizens for
Better Medicare, which has spent millions on television attacking
his Medicare plan, make public its donor lists.
</P>
<P>
   ''You know, at least there ought to be a little truth in
advertising,'' said Gore, telling the teachers a more fitting name
would be ''Citizens for Bad Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   He accused the group of ''polluting the public airwaves with
special-interest TV ads designed to deceive the American people
about a prescription drug benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   At least three of Republican George W. Bush's advisers have ties
to the drug industry: Former Rep. Vin Weber's lobbying firm clients
include the pharmaceutical association that funds the industry
group, and also Schering-Plough; former Republican National
Chairman Haley Barbour lobbies for Bristol Myers Squibb, and
Charles Black's firm lobbies for Johnson &AMP; Johnson and Smith Kline
Beecham.
</P>
<P>
   One Gore adviser, former Rep. Thomas Downey, lobbies for Merck &AMP;
Co. Another, Peter Knight, lobbied for Schering-Plough before his
firm disbanded.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has proposed a 10-year, $255 billion expansion of Medicare
that he says would cover 40 million people. He says the idea is
being fought by pharmaceutical companies eager to protect record
profits.
</P>
<P>
   ''And not all of that money is going back into research,'' Gore
said. ''In fact, millions of dollars are going into a phony
coalition called Citizens for Better Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Zielinski, a spokesman for the group, said it was reviewing
his letter, which it received Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Gore's Medicare proposal say it would be very
expensive and would actually endanger the health program.
</P>
<P>
   One of the goals of Gore's four-week swing is to rally core
Democratic voters, which he focused on in later remarks to
thousands of activists at an African-American church convention in
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are those who want to go back,'' said Gore. ''We've got
to decide to keep going and make sure no one is left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore reminded his audience that African-American unemployment
has fallen to record lows in the last eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nothing good happens without a tough fight,'' said Gore.
''We've got to choose between the people and the powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech to the teachers union, Gore also touted his plan
to expand health coverage to include all children. He said that
keeping a child healthy is key to offering a quality education.
</P>
<P>
   He was focusing on his health proposals before the teachers
union in Philadelphia, where Republicans in a little over three
weeks hold their nominating convention, and in Chicago before the
National Education Association on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As for including prescription drugs under Medicare, he said,
''You know as well as I do, prescription drugs are not at the
margins of health care. They are often the heart of treatment and
cure.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore seeks to cast Bush as siding with entrenched and powerful
interests while the Democrat sides with working families.
</P>
<P>
   Those interests include ''the big drug companies who right now
are trying to pull the wool over the country's eyes,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Drug companies argue that their profits are needed to pay for
research into new drugs, but Gore said, ''They are now spending
more money on advertising than they are on innovation.''
</P>
<P>
   He urged the group that has been running TV spots against him to
''publicly release the list of donors who are actually financing
their ads.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides arranged a conference call with Vermont Gov. Howard Dean,
a backer and a physician, to talk about the health issue in the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the area where there's the starkest difference between
the vice president and Governor Bush,'' said Dean, who contended
big drug-makers fought his own efforts to upgrade health coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ''The performance of the pharmaceutical industry has been a
disgrace,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
