<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Impeachment of Justice Recommended  </HEADLINE>
By GENE JOHNSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- A legislative committee recommended New
Hampshire's chief justice be impeached for ethics violations, a
pivotal moment in a constitutional crisis that began with a divorce
case.
</P>
<P>
   Two other Supreme Court justices under scrutiny in the same
investigation avoided punishment. Members of the House Judiciary
Committee voted earlier Wednesday not to recommend impeachment or
reprimand either.
</P>
<P>
   The committee's recommendations are expected to be put to a vote
of the full House next week.
</P>
<P>
   After six hours of debate, the House Judiciary Committee voted
that there was enough evidence that Chief Justice David Brock may
have perjured himself to warrant sending the matter to the Senate
for a trial.
</P>
<P>
   ''There seems to be a pattern here of deception. It may be over
small things, but some of these small things contributed to
obstruction of justice,'' said Keene Democrat Benjamin DePecol.
</P>
<P>
   The three judges -- Brock, Sherman Horton and John Broderick --
were accused of initially failing to blow the whistle on
then-Justice Stephen Thayer when he tried to influence the
appointment of judges to hear an appeal in his own divorce. Thayer
resigned after the scandal broke in March.
</P>
<P>
   Committee members said months of investigation and publicity had
done enough to damage Horton's and Broderick's reputations.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they haven't gotten any message from this, then they're
dead from the neck up,'' Rep. James Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   The last time a New Hampshire Supreme Court justice was
impeached was in 1790. That judge, Woodbury Langdon, described as
''arbitrary and haughty,'' resigned before his Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   At issue was whether Brock:
</P>
<P>
   -- Intervened in a state senator's case in 1987 because the
senator could help win pay raises for the bench.
</P>
<P>
   -- Placed the court's confidentiality above the need to report
misconduct by other justices.
</P>
<P>
   -- Entertained Thayer's attempt to influence his own divorce
case.
</P>
<P>
   -- Let justices take part in discussions of cases from which they
were disqualified.
</P>
<P>
   -- Perjured himself by denying under oath actions others have
insisted he took.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation began in April after Attorney General Philip
McLaughlin said that while investigating Thayer he came across
ethics violations by the rest of the court.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony before the committee last month, Brock apologized
for poor judgment but said he meant no harm. He said he knew
immediately that Thayer acted inappropriately, and he believed he
was reacting to a sensitive situation in the best possible way.
</P>
<P>
   Disclosure of Thayer's intervention prompted a group of ex-wives
of other New Hampshire judges to threaten a lawsuit in April. The
women argue they were unable to get competent lawyers or decent
divorce settlements because of their husbands' influence.
</P>
<P>
   Justices are nominated by the governor and confirmed by the
state Executive Council, an elected body that reviews nominations
and contracts. Justices serve until they reach the mandatory
retirement age of 70.
</P>
<P>
   That was an issue for some committee members in clearing Justice
Sherman Horton, who is nearing retirement. Other lawmakers said
they trusted the second judge, John Broderick, to work to reform
the court.
</P>
<P>
   Both judges were accused of protecting Thayer's actions; Horton
also was accused of improperly speaking out on the case.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you boil it all down, for me, the thing you would condemn
Justice Horton for is being a human being, and we need those on the
court,'' Rep. Andrew Peterson said.
</P>
<P>
   Broderick had said he hesitated about reporting Thayer because
he was concerned about the turmoil in Thayer's personal and
professional life.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Supreme Court:
http://www.state.nh.us/courts/supreme.htm
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Committee Investigation:
http://www.state.nh.us/gencourt/ngencourt.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-05-00 2200 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000705.0191 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mariners' Sele Named an All-Star  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Aaron Sele phoned his wife Jennifer on
Wednesday and told her to cancel the hotel reservations they had
made in San Diego for the All-Star break. They're going to Turner
Field instead.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really hadn't been thinking about it,'' the Seattle Mariners
right-hander said after making the All-Star team for the second
time. ''We were going to take our 8-month-old daughter to the beach
just to relax, have a good time and get ready for the second half.
Those were our plans up until a couple of hours ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to be a tough trip to Atlanta for them, but
anything that's exciting and fun like this, I don't want my family
to miss,''
</P>
<P>
   Mariners designated hitter Edgar Martinez will be making his
fifth All-Star trip, his first since 1997. He began Wednesday
leading the majors with 86 RBIs -- matching his 1999 total -- and was
fifth in the AL with a .352 average.
</P>
<P>
   ''The All-Star game wasn't in my mind, but it was in my mind to
have a good year and be in the playoffs,'' said the three-time AL
batting champ, who homered off Greg Maddux in the 1997 All-Star
game. ''Every time I go, it's a thrill to be with that group of
players. So it will be a thrill to be there one more time.''
</P>
<P>
   Sele and Rodriguez will be joined by teammate Alex Rodriguez,
who was voted in by the fans as the starting AL shortstop for the
third time in four years.
</P>
<P>
   Sele, 10-3 with a 4.21 ERA, was on the AL team two years ago at
Coors Field in Denver but didn't get to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be fun to pitch down there, but whether you pitch or
not, that's really not the most important thing,'' Sele said.
''It's going down there and being there for the experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
