<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Erstad, Glaus First-Time All-Stars  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Darin Erstad and Troy Glaus, complete
novices at this All-Star selection stuff, were anxiously awaiting
the end of their impromptu dugout press conferences so they could
focus on Wednesday's game.
</P>
<P>
   It probably explains why they were the only Anaheim Angels who
will be represented at this year's midsummer classic next Tuesday
night in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't play the game for numbers, we don't play the game for
individual accolades and we don't play for individual awards,''
said Glaus, a second-year third baseman hitting .293 with 23 homers
and 54 RBIs at the time of his selection.
</P>
<P>
   ''I play to win games, and whatever comes out of that is
whatever comes out of that. If we're winning, it doesn't really
matter. The bottom line is winning ballgames. If I'm voted to it,
great, because that means I was having a good year and I was doing
what my job was to help my team win.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad, the Angels' left fielder, was leading the majors with
133 hits prior to the third game of a four-game set against AL
West-leading Seattle. He also had hit 16 homers, 59 RBIs and 63
runs scored from the leadoff spot. The closest he has ever come to
an All-Star game was his television set.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's not my focus. I'm not driven by going to the All-Star
game,'' Erstad said. ''I didn't go out and play yesterday or two
months ago with the idea of having to play hard so that I could
make the All-Star game, but it's an honor and I'm happy to be
going. It's always nice to see a new ballpark and go somewhere
you've never been. It's kind of a special moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Midway through his fourth full season in the majors, the former
Nebraska Cornhuskers punter and placekicker already has surpassed
his career bests in homers and RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ''The ball looks he same to me as it's always looked,'' Erstad
said. ''I've prepared the same way I prepared last year, but this
year I'm not missing the mistakes that they're throwing. I've been
working real hard, I have a good game plan and I'm not throwing
away too many at-bats. But for whatever reason, the hits are
falling.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaus and Erstad are only the second pair of position players to
represent the Angels in an All-Star game since 1983 -- and the first
since 1995, when shortstop Gary DiSarcina and center fielder Jim
Edmonds were selected.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's something that I dreamed about since I was a little
kid,'' Glaus said. ''Every kid wants to play in the All-Star game,
and now that I get a chance to, it's something that I'll really
take to heart and enjoy. It'll be fun. I mean, I've seen it on TV,
but it's obviously different in person than it is on TV.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
