<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Book: Mayor's father was in a shootout in 1960s  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A biography of law-and-order Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani claims his father fired a gun at a man during a Brooklyn
shootout, and that Giuliani himself once slugged a guy who ogled
his date.
</P>
<P>
   The book, ''Rudy: An Investigative Biography of Rudolph
Giuliani,'' was written by Village Voice reporter Wayne Barrett and
portions of it were printed in this week's Voice. Additionally, the
publisher, Basic Books, on Wednesday gave reporters about 50 pages
from the book, due for publication next week.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has refused to comment on the book. His press secretary
refused again Wednesday to discuss the latest release from the
manuscript. Spokeswoman Sunny Mindel said, ''The mayor hasn't seen
this and therefore he has no comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrett alleges Giuliani's father, Harold Giuliani, served a
one-and-a-half year prison term in Sing Sing prison after robbing a
milkman at gunpoint in 1934, a decade before his son was born. The
book also said the elder Giuliani believed black people are
dark-skinned because God put them in ovens.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Giuliani died in 1981 at age 73 of prostate cancer, the
same disease that forced the mayor to drop his bid for a U.S.
Senate this year against Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Giuliani said his father's past died with him
and that it had nothing to do with his job as mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ''He taught me enormously important lessons, including the
lesson of being honest, which I've practiced all my life,''
Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett's book claims that while the mayor has boasted about
graduating from Manhattan College ''magna cum laude,'' he actually
graduated with lower honors, and even received a ''C'' in calculus,
according to the segments released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Livermore, Giuliani's girlfriend during college, is quoted
in the book saying that at times, the future mayor had a bad
temper.
</P>
<P>
   She recounts one instance when her former steady slugged someone
in her defense. ''The guy either said something, or made a remark
or whistled and Rudy just turned right around and punched him. His
friends pulled him off the guy. They said, 'Don't do that, what's
the matter with you?'''
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time - in the early 60s, according to the book
- Giuliani's father engaged in a gunfight on a Brighton Beach
street. The target was a mobster, the motive a loan sharking
dispute, a witness is quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett said the witness was a friend of Lewis D'Avanzo,
identified as the brother of a loanshark and that the two brothers
and the witness had gone looking for a rival along with Harold
Giuliani. When the rival was found, Giuliani shouted at him, the
other loanshark turned and shot at Giuliani's car and the mayor's
father and one of the men with him opened fire.
</P>
<P>
   There were apparently no injuries.
</P>
<P>
   A cousin of Giuliani's, Ralph Stanchi Jr., was not so lucky.
Barrett writes that Stanchi was a mob associate who specialized in
stolen vehicles, and that FBI documents link him to several
murders. He was killed by FBI agents in Brooklyn in 1977. At that
time Rudolph Giuliani was an assistant U.S. attorney in Manhattan
and had not seen the cousin since they were in grade school
together.
</P>
<P>
   Another Giuliani cousin, Joan Ellen D'Avanzo, who was raised in
the same house as Giuliani, became a junkie and was beaten to death
in 1973, according to the book.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, according to a friend of Harold Giuliani, the mayor's
father was ''disturbed by colored people'' and had devised his own
racial theories.
</P>
<P>
   ''God said the colored were not mature,'' Lina Merli told
Barrett. ''So God put them in the oven to make them mature. But
God, he forgot to take them out, so colored people came out
black.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
