<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ocean liner in fender bender with two military ships  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - The world-renowned ocean liner Queen Elizabeth
II was in a minor Hudson River fender-bender with two military
ships as it tried to enter a Manhattan slip Wednesday morning, the
Coast Guard said.
</P>
<P>
   One day after all three crafts participated in Operation Sail
2000, the QE2 accidentally bumped the Japanese warship Kashima,
which in turn banged into the British warship H.M.S. Manchester,
said Coast Guard spokesman Tony Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   The QE2 was entering its docking place at the passenger terminal
on Manhattan's West Side when the accident occurred, Riordan said.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Good, a spokesman for Cunard Line Ltd., which owns the
famous ship, said one of the stern tugs was pulled away from the
QE2 by a strong current, and the other was unable to hold the ship
on course.
</P>
<P>
   The damage was minimal: scraped paint on the Kashima, scrapes
and a damaged railing on the QE2, scrapes and some bent metal on
the Manchester.
</P>
<P>
   Good said the QE2's captain, Paul Wright, boarded the Kashima
for a look after he finished docking.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was an admiral on board who said, 'Not to worry.' They
felt that it was an honor to be kissed by the queen,'' Good said.
</P>
<P>
   No injuries were reported in the accident, which remained under
Coast Guard investigation. The two warships were moored when the
small-scale crash occurred.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
