<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mayor, chancellor meet on first day of summer school  </HEADLINE>
By TIMOTHY WILLIAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - On the first day of summer school for more than
200,000 children who fell behind during the regular school year,
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Schools Chancellor Harold Levy appeared
together publicly for the first time Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   They appeared intent on healing their rift.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who had once vehemently opposed Levy's appointment to
the top schools post, credited him with trying to turn around a
system beset by poor test scores, crowded classrooms and labor
troubles.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, 319,000 students - almost one-third of the
district's 1.1 million students - have been either required or
encouraged to enroll in summer courses because of failing or
marginal performance.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is an attempt to try to turn the system into one with
much, much higher standards,'' Giuliani said at a news conference
in the library of a Washington Heights elementary school, P.S. 48.
''It won't be easy, but I think the chancellor and the Board of
Education are moving in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Levy, standing by the mayor's side, returned the kind words. He
credited Giuliani with pushing to end so-called social promotion
and said the school system can be vastly improved.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mayor, with your support, I think we can do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the men - both of whom enjoy the glare of media attention
and of having the final word - also affected the over-polite
manners of people still sizing one another up.
</P>
<P>
   Several times, the two awkwardly deferred to each other, and
when asked whether they had met privately to discuss educational
issues and how they were getting along, they politely declined to
answer.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Giuliani half-kiddingly told Levy, ''Don't answer
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, when Levy left the room and the mayor had center stage,
Giuliani acknowledged that the two disagreed on the issue of merit
pay - a proposal bitterly opposed by teachers but insisted upon by
the Giuliani administration during the current labor contract
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   After being pressed about his relationship with Levy, Giuliani
answered circumspectly, saying, ''I think we have a very
constructive relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   How the two men get along is being closely watched because
Giuliani has had a hand in forcing out the last two schools
chancellors. He also tried to derail Levy's ascendance to
chancellor by challenging both the lawyer's educational
qualifications, and business ties to a Board of Education member
who backed him.
</P>
<P>
   When it became clear that the Board of Education would approve
Levy despite Giuliani's objections, the mayor instructed his
appointees and allies on the board to back Levy. The board did so
unanimously in May.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
