<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Law Allows Spanking of Kids  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Parents and teachers can spank children under
Canadian law, but the issue should be reviewed because public
attitudes have changed, a judge ruled Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Ontario Superior Court Judge David McCombs
rejected a challenge by child advocacy groups of the law that they
said violated the constitutional rights of children.
</P>
<P>
   Section 43 of the Criminal Code says ''every school teacher,
parent or person standing in place of a parent is justified in
using force by way of correction ... if force does not exceed what
is reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   McCombs upheld the law, saying he did not believe it infringed
on children's rights. But, he added, it may be time to review the
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ''The evidence shows that public attitudes toward corporal
punishment of children are changing,'' McCombs said in his written
decision. ''There is a growing body of evidence that even mild
forms of corporal punishment do no good and may cause harm.''
</P>
<P>
   A public opinion poll released in December found most Canadians
opposed making spanking a criminal offense.
</P>
<P>
   Children's rights advocates say the law offers a defense for
teachers, parents and babysitters charged with assaulting
youngsters, and has been used to justify hitting children and
teen-agers with belts, electrical cords and plastic rulers.
</P>
<P>
   But Barbara Sargent, president of the Ontario Teachers
Federation, defended the so-called spanking law as a critical tool
for educators.
</P>
<P>
   ''What section 43 did and will continue to do is enable teachers
to maintain some kind of discipline and balance in the classroom,''
Sargent said Wednesday. ''Teachers will be able to maintain
discipline in a fair and judicial way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian Foundation for Children, Youth and Law argued the
law violates the Charter of Rights and Freedom by making children
the only group of citizens that can be legally assaulted for
reasons other than self-defense or protecting others.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Canada's attorney general said parents should be
allowed to discipline children without facing criminal charges. In
its court brief, however, the federal government said it agreed
that other forms of discipline should be encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, individual states determine laws regarding
corporal punishment and several states have prohibited allowing
spankings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-05-00 2344 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
