<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 23:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Female Bishops Topic in AME Meeting  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN NOLAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- Even though women outnumber men 3 to 1 in the
African Methodist Episcopal Church, the denomination has never had
a female bishop in its 213-year history.
</P>
<P>
   But as AME's 46th general conference began Wednesday, officials
said there could be enough support this year to get one of the two
female candidates elected as one of the church's 19 bishops.
Elections for the 2.5 million-member denomination will be held
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Wouldn't it be great if we could get one?'' said Delores
Williams, 51, a delegate from Panama City, Fla. ''Whoever she is,
I'm for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Delegates to the weeklong conference gave Vice President Al Gore
a warm reception Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   In a 40-minute speech, Gore emphasized education and health care
but also touched on many traditional Democratic issues -- gun
controls, the minimum wage and free, universal pre-school.
</P>
<P>
   He told the delegates that the Clinton administration deserved
credit for raising incomes in black households and that they could
keep the nation ''on the right track'' by helping elect him.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have made good progress, but you ain't seen nothin' yet,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore asked delegates to ''join with me'' in his quest for the
presidency and received a standing ovation, with the band striking
up the hymn ''Victory Is Mine'' as he left the podium.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he lifted up some excellent points,'' said T.R.
Goyins, a delegate from Roselle, N.J. ''He hit on things that are
going to feed the inner soul.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Carolyn Tyler Guidry, who supervises 19 AME churches in
Los Angeles, and the Rev. Vashti M. McKenzie, pastor of a church in
Baltimore, are among 41 candidates for two bishop positions vacated
by retirement. Guidry stood for election as bishop in 1996;
McKenzie is making her first run.
</P>
<P>
   ''We let the men lead the household and the church,'' said Doris
Hamilton, 57, a delegate from Atlanta. ''But it's a new century,
and things are changing.''
</P>
<P>
   Several organizations within the AME Church have urged election
of a female bishop. The United Methodist Church and the Episcopal
Church have had female bishops for years.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in Philadelphia in 1787, the AME Church has members in
the United States, Africa, Canada, England and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   The AME general conference meets every four years and governs
the denomination.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the AME's 19 districts is led by a bishop, who also
serve on a leadership council for the denomination. A majority of
the 1,800 delegates is required to elect a bishop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-05-00 2345 </TRAILER>
