<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Parties Clash After Election  </HEADLINE>
By JULIE WATSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHIMALHUACAN, Mexico (AP) -- Three days after the electoral upset
of Mexico's ruling party, its loyalists clashed with opposition
activists in several cities Wednesday in rock-throwing skirmishes
that left a dozen people injured.
</P>
<P>
   Buses also were burned in several clashes in Mexico state, which
surrounds Mexico City, after opposition groups accused the ruling
party of electoral fraud as ballots were being re-counted in local
races.
</P>
<P>
   ''They've always done this (fraud) here, but now the people are
tired,'' said Felipe Castillo Rocha, an electrician and opposition
activist punched in the jaw during a clash in the suburb of
Chimalhuacan.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rest of Mexico voted for a change, and we want to be part
of it, too. We're not going to let them get away with this.''
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear who started the fighting, which began amid a show
of force by local supporters of the ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party, or PRI, which lost the presidency for the
first time in 71 years Sunday but hung on to some local
governments.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the day, about 1,000 PRI supporters gathered outside
buildings in several cities where electoral officials were carrying
out a ballot re-count expected to conclude Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We won legitimately, and for those who have their doubts, the
proof that the people voted for the PRI is this concentration of
people here today,'' said Jesus Tolentino, the PRI candidate for
mayor of Chimalhuacan, as he stood atop a pickup truck in the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ''Although on a national level the PRI lost, we here in
Chimalhuacan haven't lost the faith.''
</P>
<P>
   The PRI, which is struggling to re-group and survive after
Sunday's crushing defeat at the polls, apparently held on to the
Chimalhuacan mayorship, according to preliminary results.
</P>
<P>
   Other skirmishes broke out in the northern Mexico City suburb of
Ecatepec and in the city of Ixtlahuaca.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
