<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-05 23:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dallas trustees fire Superintendent Bill Rojas  </HEADLINE>
By KELLIE B. GORMLY
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) - The Dallas school trustees decided Wednesday to
fire Superintendent Bill Rojas, ending the tenure of the fourth
district leader in five years and multiple disputes that have
erupted since Rojas began work in August.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the superintendent's offer last week to resign,
the board invoked the ''good rapport'' clause, citing poor
communication between Rojas and the board members.
</P>
<P>
   Rojas, who grew up in the South Bronx, spent most of his 31-year
educational career in New York City school system. School officials
in New York have described him as sometimes forceful and outspoken
but very devoted to children.
</P>
<P>
   By firing Rojas, the district pays him $90,000 in severance pay.
Accepting his resignation could have cost the district $520,000 in
pay for the remainder of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Rojas was hired as the fourth chief in five years and replaced
Yvonne Gonzalez, who was sentenced to federal prison for embezzling
$16,000 in district funds. He was reportedly the nation's
highest-paid superintendent, earning a base salary of $260,000.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to school board president Roxan Staff last week,
Rojas wrote that the trustees tried to ''micromanage'' him and that
his relationships with many of them are beyond repair. He said he
hopes his resignation will end the power struggles and enable the
board to focus on improving education.
</P>
<P>
   The board has voted longtime educator Robert Payton to act as
interim superintendent effective immediately. Payton, who has
worked for the district 35 years, was in charge of the city's nine
sub-districts.
</P>
<P>
   Staff said the board hopes to have a permanent superintendent
named by the end of August.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders of two Dallas business groups have urged board
members to hire a permanent replacement within 30 days, because
they said an interim superintendent would only trigger more chaos
within the district.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders from the Greater Dallas Chamber of Commerce and the
Dallas Citizens Council Tuesday urged the board to choose the
replacement with the assistance of a three-person advisory
committee and to accept Rojas' resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, members of the local chapter of LULAC - League of
United Latin American Citizens - are calling on the Texas Education
Agency to take over the Dallas schools, which have a Hispanic
student population of about 54 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Although LULAC does not support Rojas, the group assigns equal
blame to the trustees for the district's problems, said Jesse Diaz,
president of Council 4496. At least five or six of the trustees
should be removed because they are ''dysfunctional'' and simply
cannot get along with each other, Diaz said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a cancer on the school board,'' he said. ''The only
way we're going to get rid of it is to remove it.''
</P>
<P>
   School and community leaders hoped by hiring Rojas, who is of
Puerto Rican descent, he would bring the same success to Dallas
that he had working with minority groups in San Francisco. Rojas
was credited for raising the test scores of blacks and Hispanics
during his seven-year tenure as superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   Trustees have been at odds with Rojas for months over a lack of
communication and their worries about the possibility of excessive
spending in the next budget, including the hiring of the for-profit
Edison Schools Inc. to run several schools.
</P>
<P>
   Some trustees claim Rojas' spending commitments have created an
estimated $52 million shortfall in the district budget.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
