<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gov. Signs Teacher Incentive Bills  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- In a bid to draw teachers to
California and keep them, Gov. Gray Davis on Wednesday approved
more than $2.4 billion in educational incentives, including higher
starting pay and better benefits for teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are aimed at improving student performance and
easing California's teacher shortage.
</P>
<P>
   Minimum starting salaries will rise from $32,000 to $34,000,
and, teachers who have at least four years experience at public or
private schools will get a new tax credit of $250 to $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now it can truly be said that California values teachers and
it can truly be said that if you want to teach, teach in
California,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   The state expects to need 300,000 additional teachers over the
next decade.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also signed a bill adding $100 million for a
program that gives up to $25,000 to teachers whose students meet
higher goals on the state achievement test. And he approved
cost-of-living increases and bonuses of up to $20,000 for teachers
who agree to work at low-performing schools.
</P>
<P>
   Davis initially sought to exempt teachers from California's
income tax, but lawmakers rejected that idea.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
